name: The Aggro Crag
description: Sit start at the left of the craggy side of Tall Wall, left hand juggy side pull, right hand crimp, move to the big pointy triangle block and straight up.

name: Always Two There Are
description: The incredible, close to classic compression line next to Darth Maul on the big eggy boulder up the stream bed. Start sitting on the rock under the black sidepull crimp, squeezing the other side of the block with the left. Throw the right up for a sloper, shimmy up to the duck bill hold and throw for the top out holds. Pretty bad feet throughout and very steep, super fun!

name: Bath and a Half
description: Start under the little roof with a bunch of holds in reach. Jug crimp for the right and overhead sloper jug for the left. Gain matched jug to the left. Hoist the bulge and gain jug ledge to topout! Super fun!

name: The Battle of Waterloo
description: Update. A large thorn bush is now growing over the topout.   This boulder is right on Waterloo Rd but between mile markers 4 and 5. It's easily visible from the road and is only 30 yards or so from a convenient pull off. Just hop out and enjoy this one-off, very fun problem. And its companions farther up the hill...  Start standing, left hand on a big jug and left foot on the orange triangle. The shelf is off except this orange triangle. Move right to a matched crimp and up to a slopey jug and more fair holds. Top out to the right of the live bushes.

name: Big Fat Pauly
description: Start sitting in the juggy features, move right, gain the Crescent hold and use the off width chimney to top out.

name: Billy Joel
description: See picture for Route Line. Sit start to the left with jugs. Big move up and right to two good edges. Traverse right using little pockets that are head height, one is about 1 foot above the other. Continue to move right to a nice side pull and jugs, then top out.  I’m a new climber so grade may be off. Found the route which has clearly been done before but just wanted to add it to this site.

name: Brake Check
description: On Cracked Boulder's vertical face, directly above Cross Stitch. Start standing with left hand in a big undercling and right on a slopey sidepull. Up to the big rail and commit to an interesting topout.

name: Cheddar Stacks
description: Big sharp triangular shelf is the start. Straight up on nice holds.

name: Cirrus
description: To the right of Cumulus, start on jugs and move up over the bulge, trending slightly right for the top out.

name: Cognitive Dissonance
description: Next to the Pea is this fun little problem that starts standing on the pointy jug and a choice of holds, then a move or two to the right and over the slopey bulge.

name: Count Dooku
description: Start as Always Two but turn right around the bulge with funky foot beta, matching the lip slope crimps and bumping up to juggy crack.

name: Crack Epidemic
description: hidden behind cracked boulder is a rock inside the crevice with extremely chossy holds that could break. Be prepared to up the grade rating every time you crack a hold.

name: Cracked
description: The cracked boulder has a few easy lines but it's a good landmark and a nice warm up on the way to bigger and better things. On the downhill side is Brake Check (V1) and Allamuchy Layback (V0) on the downhill arete/crack as seen in the beta picture.

name: Cross Stitch
description: This wall is directly under the Cracked Boulder and contains three or four problems depending on how you topout. On the left is Cross Stitch A, starting laid back on nice features, topout over the left of the start (V1). The middle is Cross Stitch B, start sitting holding the big block feature and topout following the crack left, over the bulge (V1), or topout to the right standing on the start block (V0). The right side, starting on the grippy sloper pull on the arete and the big crimp for the right hand is Turntable (V0).

name: Cumulus
description: If you approach from the rear of the boulders by hiking up the unmarked trail, then forking right into the woods at the first footbridge, this wall is your first stop on the left... Cumulus is a very sharp sit start on the left of the wall pictured. Hard and kind of awkward even using the cheat block under the face but the sit move is a hard 3, comparable to the strength of Mr. Miyagi sit. Two fingers crimpy pointy thing on the start block for the left hand, right on the slopey side of the block. Throw right to the gnarly crimper and side pull jugs from there.

name: Darth Lemur
description: You start at the lowest point of the over-hang with both hands on mild slopers, left toe on an edge underneath the over-hang, and right heel hooked on the side of the over-hang.  Traverse the over-hang to the left, and then slab directly up the apex.

name: Darth Maul
description: Start standing with hands far apart on opposing side pulls, find a couple intermediate holds, then left hand to a large sloping pinch near the top. Top out without using the chock rock. Cue Imperial March

name: Darth Vader
description: Directly around back and up the hill from Darth Maul. Start matched on the big jug at eye level, committed moves on really sweet crimps.

name: Dooku Stand
description: Match the slope crimps and toe hook, utilizing a triple bump to get into the crack jug. Stand start to Count Dooku.

name: Doorknob
description: A triangular flake under a big jug to the right. Sit, toeing into the small flakes near the ground with your hands in the large flake. Move up to the giant jug and topout with your choice of holds and a small mantle.

name: Drop Top
description: A really fun boulder but a crappy landing zone. Make sure your pads are set and your spotter ready. Do not use the shelf!    This one has a flaked rail on the left side and a few challenging slopers with a committing top out. Sit start under the rail and move to the right with a couple slopers and confident feet. Top out over the crack, do not turn right around the top.

name: The Duke of Wellington
description: On the downhill corner, start standing on the little shelf, left hand on a weird crimp overhead, right hand undercling in the crack. Move up to a slopey hold then right to a big crimp and intermediate holds.

name: Dumptruck and Firetruck
description: Good warm up, easy goes it.

name: Fickle Finger of Fate
description: A little rougher than it looks but a pretty fun little slab above Lesser Magick. A couple of crimps and bad feet at the start, move up to the characteristic finger feature and top out over the highest point to the left.

name: The Fly
description: At the back of the Karate Kid boulder, start left hand undercling, right hand side pull. Straight up, top out with the slopey flake.

name: The Initiate
description: Start standing on two sweet crimps, one has a triangular shape. Variety of holds up to the little pocket, move straight up on crystal holds for the topout. Careful of the small gap between the two slabs at the landing.

name: The Karate Kid
description: Start standing in front of the bulge to the right of Mr Miyagi with sharp sidepulls but not on the cleaved chunk on the ground. Hoist the bulge and top out over the tallest point. Popper climbed this rock in untied timberlands hahaha

name: The King of Prussia
description: Start standing on the little shelf, right hand in the crack undercling and left on the weird overhead crimp. Move right along the crack, continue up the crack to top out.

name: Kitchen Sink
description: Start on a big black undercling jug, follow multiple jug lines around the right arete and top out as per Bath and a Half on the right most jug ledge. Pretty much the most fun easy bouldering in Allamuchy so far.

name: Ladder To Heaven
description: Sit start on crimps at the bottom of the boulder on the slightly overhung side. Bump right hand over to the crimp rail on the right, match with the left hand and move to the top for a slopey finish.

name: Leopard Print Pumps
description: Layback along the jugs in the horizontal crack, then top out through the cave, V1.  Sit start begins on the knob to the right, adding one strenuous move which is easier with a heel/toe cam if you can find it V2/3

name: Lesser Magick
description: Big triangular slab behind the Spear. Just two strenuous moves. Start right hand on a nice sidepull, left on the arete jugs. Move up to the notch with your right hand. The move is a bit reachy but the hold is good. Sweet spine feature for the left hand on top out.

name: Little Bitta Layback
description: This one is a hidden gem. Go up the streambed, pass Darth Maul and Oscar the Grouch, hook a right up the steep hill near Big Fat Pauly and continue up to some of the largest formations in the bluff.    Get up on the big flat shelf to start the thin layback and gain a variety of good holds to continue to a heady top out. This one should be taken with care.

name: Look Mom, No Hands!
description: A sweet slab with varying angles, features (or the lack thereof) and endless possibilities for no hand ascents and warm up runs. Visible from the unmarked trail, about 75 yards from the parking lot.

name: Mike O'Malley
description: Aggro Crag Extension. Start on the small block next to the craggy side of Tall Wall as low and left as possible. Move up and right on the block and get up the craggy face. Heady but the committed move is low, very fun. Check your landing, have good spotters for the top out.

name: Mind Kontrol Ultra
description: Starts standing facing uphill on two crimps and good feet. Make a long move up left, then up the arete on nice holds to a big pointy jug feature and along the top rail with super sweet holds and moves the whole way to the topout. The thin flake on the left face should be avoided since it seems to be very hollow.

name: Mr. Miyagi
description: A one move wonder with an easy top out, Sit start on the left side of the Karate Kid bulge. With your left hand in a slippery crystalline pocket, right hand on a sharp crimp, both feet off to the right on a small shelf. Deadpoint to an adequate handhold or the nice jug, then top out over the tallest point. Recently, Alex Martin sent Miyagi with a static sequence! Alternatively: stand start right hand in the jug, left hand in the crystalline pocket V0

name: My Brother's Block
description: In the middle of the talus in the stream bed on the way up to Tall Wall, The Spear etc. A short block with a couple shelves and one of those slopey topouts we love to hate.

name: Napoleon
description: Sit start under the Battle of Waterloo with both feet in the crack and both hands on the shelf, right hand to a big jug side pull. The rest of the shelf to the left is off. Move straight up with good feet and a long move to the big crimp with left hand. Up to nice holds for the topout.

name: Nimbus
description: Highball above Big Fat Pauly, near Cumulus. Start standing left hand on the arete, right in a jug, move to a right hand sidepull and commit to a couple weird sloping crimps near the top. Be very cautious on this one.

name: Oreos
description: A really cool set of moves gets you started on this one. Potential for toe and heel hooks, depending on your size. The topout is the crux, but you can stand on the big block for a rest before attempting it. Avoid using rocks delineated by the vertical cracks on the Cross Stitch boulder for the most interesting climb.

name: Oscar the Grouch
description: A serious but easy highball slab, Oscar is messy at first glance, the fear junkies will enjoy some exposure!

name: Padlock
description: Start on the big triangle flake of Doorknob but deadpoint to the big square cutout with left hand and top out without using the big jug to the right.

name: The Pea
description: Up the unmarked trail and trending right at the two forks, up the yellow trail to the very top of the Allamuchy Ridge is this unmistakable 20 ft monster. It's called the Pea by locals as a sort of sarcastic poke at the large size of this rock. There are at least two good lines on it but the downclimb is tough. The front has a stand start with some sweet pulls where a crack formed; follow the weakness to the top, about V2. The back of the boulder has a few moderate and tall slab lines with a gnarly fall under them, seem to be about V2 or harder. Between these two is a shelved problem that should go at V1. Be super careful about getting off this rock.

name: Penny Loafers
description: Under LPP, climb the vertical face with crimps to start and move up to the sloper top. Move left and topout around the highest point of the slabby rock.

name: Pickle
description: Off the teal trail all the way up the steep hill after the streambed. Start with both feet and hands as far right and low as possible,  work up to the left into or past the slot, then utilizing some intermediate holds on the way to a big flake at the topout trending leftward. Stay on the front face. The landing zone can be dangerous.

name: Project: Darth Sidious
description: Start on Always Two There Are and finish up Sidious Stand with some awesome movement around the lip.

name: Project: Rocket Nozzle
description: An absolutely superb line on the cliff band above Skanderbeg's Shield. Start on low side pull jug, move through beautiful holds and a beta intensive sequence to a sloped shelf on the left. Burl your way over the lip!

name: Project: Yatta!
description: Start on two credit card sized crimps or even the side pull pinches with a little foot edge. Use a terrible intermediate near the lip or just jump from the start. Really hard single move. Still a project.

name: Red Stilhettos
description: On the knobby holds to the right of Leopard Print Pumps. Move up and then left across the ledge slopers. The jug holds on LPP are off, smear feet. Top out through the cave.

name: Rubber Ducky
description: To left left of Doorknob, start in low jugs and gain slopers and then the top out. A tough little lowball to warm up.

name: Sack Up
description: right next to crack epidemic on the same rocks start standing on a small foot, a crimp for the left hand and an under cling for the right. move to a small pocket then match on a sloper to top out jug.

name: Scurvy Direct
description: On the Scurvy boulder, start sitting under the prow and reach left hand up to a fair crimp. Right hand starts on the very sharp crimp seam. The boulder to the left is off, no jamming in the crack or smearing to start or topout. Pull on and toss left to the better crimp, get over the prow with use of a slopey crimp and iffy mantle. Starting with both hands a bit lower might add a grade but it's awkward.

name: Scurvy Traverse
description: Start at the right with feet near the ground, a right hand side pull and a crimp for your left hand up top. Move along the top then make a wide left foot move to the little shelf. Around the corner for a nice crimp and mantle out.

name: Sensei
description: Mr. Miyagi's sit-start but move to the rail on the left and top out the vertical face next to Wax On.

name: Sidious Stand
description: Starting to the right of Dooku on good side pulls above head height, left heel hook and lock off to the little horn hold.

name: Skanderbeg's Big Toe
description: On the backside of the boulder that his shield fell from, the hero's big toe sticks out from the arete. Feet under the lip, both hands on the big flat rail and use the arete hold and a simple mantle to get over the face.

name: Skanderbeg's Shield
description: Sit start begins under the shelf ledges and goes straight up. Left hand start on small sharp crimp, right hand on gaston ledge. Project line begins on crescent hold, farther to the left and connects one very intense move to join the pure line.

name: Sketch Pad
description: A little slabby face that will force some footwork and balance.

name: Space Jam
description: The kind of climb you can't find but wish you could. I stumbled into a new formation, smack in the middle of the woods, half a mile off trail. It's easiest to find this one from the road. The best way I can describe the location is between the Scout Reservation and the parking lot for the main wall on Waterloo Rd sits a private residence in the State Park. Far to the right of this home (be respectful!) is a series of stone walls, hidden by brush but visible in the winter. Up the hill past the walls are some obvious formations.    Start at the right side of the cave and follow the ledge and cracks diagonal left to a heady top out over a fair landing. Bring a couple pads and a buddy. Top out over the large crack with a bunch of choices for jamming then mantle.

name: Spear of Destiny
description: Standing, left hand sidepull, right hand Gaston. Go to the left around the small tree growing in the top.

name: Stay Together for the Kids
description: A fun juggy undercling start on a split boulder about 50 yards up the stream bed from Cracked. A fair landing. Good warm up

name: Tall Wall Traverse AKA Bread Slice
description: Tall Wall is ten minutes up the stream bed. The main face is a crimpy wall, The Initiate (V2), the adjacent side is The Aggro Crag/Mike O'Malley (V1). Some folks I talked to like to call this block the Bread Slice and mentioned that the traverse line was a fun challenge when they were out with their friends; Start sitting at the short block on the left and move right, onto the craggy face, then around the corner onto the clean face, then to the far right. Some of that group I talked to also mentioned a friend of theirs bolted a cave up in the woods behind these features but upon inspection the ropeable climb(s) would require some cams and guts.

name: Wax Off
description: At the back of the Karate Kid boulder, start on the knife and move right, up the awkward staircase and top out over the big slopey flake.

name: Wax On
description: At the steepest bulge on the Karate Kid boulder, start two hands on crimps next to the big knob, or alternatively start by hugging the arete with a choice of crimpy holds. Move left and find a blind sloper or crimp sidepull on the corner of the bulge with left hand, and continue to some sketchy slopers and crimps but solid feet on the vertical portion. A little tree sits on the topout.

name: Weekend Express
description: Low start on left arete with left hand on 3/4 pad ledge and right in low, thin seam. Pull on and establish feet and make move out right to flat ledge. Work feet and top out.

name: Yosh!
description: Sit start on sharp crimps.  Work right and up on crimps then dyno for the top!

name: Z Cracks
description: A couple of 5.6 to 5.9 lines and easy traverses to warm up on in the back area near Big Fat Pauly

name: Tit porn
description: Cave boulder problem

name: Cave Direct
description: the main problem goes out the roof of the cave following a crack on the inside roof. Start from the hanging block in the back of the cave. A toprope is recommended and a spotter is necessary.

name: Green sky
description: this route has to offer a lot of very good practice for people new to bouldering but is still difficult for people with experience. See picture for hand and foot placement. Some of the holds and feet might be wet so a blow torch is a good idea for drying wet spots.

name: Knocking at Your Back Door
description: Bad feet for Dyno move to final finish hold. Top out is not necessary.

name: Vinny’s Reach
description: start under the rock, reach behind, topout

name: Cling Zing
description: start at obvious undercling, head up along arete

Start behind the left-most tree near the base. Move up and slightly left to a small overhang. Move up and left to pass the blank looking face on the left. traverse a little right, climb a flake to the top.

Start about 5-6 feet left of the right corner at the base of a flake. Follow the flake to the small overhang. Lay back or jam the crack and follow it to a ledge. Either continue straight up through the off-width, or traverse left to a flake, and climb to the top.  I believe the tree originally described to be at the base of this climb is no longer present.
Crack midway between two trees at base.

name: 5.7 (center)
description: Crack just left of tree. The blank face between this route and Muddy Waters to the left likely still waits for a first ascent.

name: 5.7 (left)
description: Crack 6 feet right of European Vacation

name: Born in the USA
description: Climb seam, then face behind left tree. Protection available in crack to left.

name: European Vacation
description: The left most climb on the cliff, goes up a slab a few feet left of the arete, staying slightly left of an old bolt without a hanger.

name: Muddy Waters
description: The next and very conspicuous crack to the left. The smaller cracks just to the left of this are not as interesting.

name: Spanglish
description: Slab 10 feet right of tree at right hand side of the base.
Starting under the right end of the overhangs, climb easily up, step right, then up easy slabs to the top. Stay away from the overhangs.
Right facing corner separating Right Wall from Main Wall.

name: 5.5 (Main Wall)
description: Climb a tiered, right facing corner system that begins 12' above the ground.

name: 5.6 (Left of Hourglass)
description: Climb up through a notch in the overhang about 12 feet left of Hourglass.
Climb the face, staying left of hourglass at all times.

name: 5.7 (Main Wall, Right)
description: Start is about 5 feet left of a tree at the base of the climb and immediately to the right of 5.5 (Main Wall). The first few moves are tricky. Climb straight up the face between two right facing corners. Top out either at the first ledge just right of the 5.5 (Main Wall) anchors or continue up another 15 feet or so to the tree.
Left most crack, just right of Blow Out
Traverse from left to right under overhangs.
Arete to left of right facing corner
Double crack at extreme right end of Right wall.

name: A Touch Too Much
description: Walk 20 feet right from the right end of the Right wall and up the hill 30 feet to a rear wall, south facing, with a small tree growing out of the face. Climb to top, staying right of tree.

name: A Year in the Life
description: Approach a now missing bolt from good holds on the right. Traverse left onto a blank face, away from any good holds on the right. Head for the next bolt hole, then towards the tp. Small cams and nuts useful above the former last bolt.

name: A Year in the Life, Variation 1 Direct Start
description: Climb the very blank face straight up to the first bolt hole without using any good holds on or near the corner to the right. Head for next bolt hole and to top.

name: A Year in the Life, Variation 2, Left Start
description: Begin several feet left of the direct start, then climb delicately up and right on small holds. After reaching first bolt or bolt hole, proceed up.

name: Blow Out
description: Steep face just right of right facing corner. Gear is useful above bolt. There used to be 2 bolts, but now there is only 1.

name: Evening Visitor
description: Start: Find Easiest way up arete/corner system to the left of "A Touch to Much". Climb up to the left of the upper face of "A.T.T.M". continue up to wide ledge above the face of "A.T.T.M" and set up a TR for "A.T.T.M". Climb can continue to top.

name: Foreign Invasion
description: Start at a small, left facing corner and climb the face past a bolt to a small horizontal crack. Continue to the top.

name: Hourglass
description: Begin at a vertical crack about 6 feet left of Foreign Invasion. Climb through the hourglass crack formation, then past several small corners to top.

name: Main Wall Traverse
description: Traverse main wall in either direction

name: Roof Route
description: Start up the slab to a small overlap, then continue up to a roof. pull the roof in the center and continue on easier thin slab climbing. Look up and left for a left facing corner with hand crack, adds one last good move to the climb.

name: Welcome to Waterloo
description: Start on left side of the Main wall (right of Hourglass and left of Foreign Invasion)and aim for a short vertical crack about 15 ft. up. Climb up then step right to the horizontal letterbox. Set good gear then diagonal up and right to above A Year in the Life. Set anchors or top out and walkoff right. My favorite climb at Allamuchy.
Start directly in front of the tree near the base. climb the obvious crack system straight to the top.

Start at a right slanting crack that starts at face level about 8 feet right of a tree growing near the base. climb straight up to a stance. Step left, then pass on the right side of the tree growing out of the cliff and continue to top.

name: 5.5 Arete
description: Climb arete left of Salty Tears.

name: Salty Tears (left of bolt)
description: Start directly beneath a bolt. Climb up to the bolt and clip it. Climb the thing face between the bolt and the left arete to top.

name: Salty Tears (right of bolt)
description: Start directly beneath the bolt, climb to the bolt and clip it. Follow better holds to the right of bolt to top.
Start in a large, obvious, left facing corner. Climb up, move out onto the arete and proceed up the crack.
Start in a large, obvious, left facing corner. climb up left through a crack in the roof.
Start below the right end of the low overhang at a dirty, vertical crack. Climb up and left.

name: Chin Chaver
description: Start below the center of the low overhang at a jutting, tapering horizontal hold that feels hollow. Haul yourself over the awkward overhang.

name: Raincoats and Candles
description: Climb the crack at the far right end of this section of wall. Pass fixed small blue camalot and proceed to top.

name: Stoke the Locals
description: Start below the left end of the low overhang at a large, jutting hold about four feet right of an arete. Without using the arete, climb to top.

name: Lead Roof
description: Start mid wall just below foot ledge. Follow small dihedral to 2 roof system with a vertical crack in the center. After passing roof top out on first ledge or continue to top of wall.

name: Cast-less Point
description: Some fun moves.  . . . The two pitches can be combined, but then if Top-Roping in the normal way from the bottom, using a normal dynamic rope, if the climber falls near the bottom, then due to rope stretch the fall could be longer or harder and the climber could be injured. So if trying it that way, likely better to instead use a static (or "semi-static") rope. Or at least keep the climber under tension while close to the bottom of the route.  P1: Start at base of left-trending inside corner facing left, which is below left from obvious down-protruding nose about 25 ft up. Up the inside corner to just right of the obvious down-protruding nose. Up into the gully, then up its left side (with hands using right side of nose rock). When hands can reach a smaller down-protruding nose, got up on the right side of ridge which rises up from big lower down-protruding nose). Finish with gully + ridge by passing right of two old light-brown peeling-bark cedar trees, and just left of old light-brown peeling-bark cedar tree which splits low into two trunks.  P2: Continue up slab passing just left of old light-brown peeling-bark cedar tree with branches pointing downward. Finish to right-hand flat block 15-20 ft right of the big dead tree stump and just left of small living tree on summit platform.  warning: The rock on and near this route has not been climbed much yet, and some of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber or someone setting up top anchor.  . . . (Lots of vegetation on this rock as of 2018. Be prepared when climbing to navigate around protruding trees and branches, and dealing with holds slippery with grass, lichen, moss, dirt).  name: The southern part of the land once managed by the Smiley family has a great viewpoint on a big rock formation which looked a bit like the walls of a castle (unlike the platform at top of this route), and has a carriage road going over the top of it.

name: Dividing Ramp
description: Obvious line that marks the left boundary between sector Smiley Face and upper part of sector Smiley Slopes. Can be used to access harder short routes. Fairly vegetated as of 2018.  Start by two large trees on a small depressed platform at the of the ridge which rises above the big slanting roof. . . ? (project: This route would be more independent (and useful?) if it were reached from one of the "Notch" routes of sector Smiley Face, but we have not checked that yet.) ?   Step up right onto slab, then up the left edge of that slab (shared with the route "Ski Bonticou") to reach the base of steep outside corner. Go past left side of that corner, under short steep face with interesting features (the routes BontiQteeth + BontiQtree). Finish up to top of ramp.  warning: The rock on and near this route has not been climbed much yet, and some of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber or someone setting up top anchor.  . . . (Lots of vegetation on this rock as of 2018. Be prepared when climbing to navigate around protruding trees and branches, and dealing with holds slippery with grass, lichen, moss, dirt).

name: Fissure of the Middle Way
description: Interesting moves in different rock situations.  . . . The two pitches can be combined, but then if Top-Roping in the normal way from the bottom, using a normal dynamic rope, if the climber falls near the bottom, then due to rope stretch the fall could be longer or harder and the climber could be injured. So if trying it that way, likely better to instead use a static (or "semi-static") rope. Or at least keep the climber under tension while close to the bottom of the route.  P1: Start about 10-15 feet right from the ridge of the "big slanting roof" rock, just left of a thick two-trunk tree which is just above left of a thick one-trunk tree. Roughty straight up over some short thin slanting cracks, then up a 4-6-inch wide straight crack to its top. Next traverse horixontal Right 10-15 feet to the bottom of a big left-facing inside corner. Up this corner 10-15 feet to a weakness above right. . .  Variation (thoughtful + harder perhaps 5.7): Instead of going up inside the corner, climb the steeper face just right of the corner, up the left half ot fhe face to a tree in the center of the slab above.  At weakness exit from the inside corner up right onto slab (5.3), to a tree in ins center..  P2: Roughly straight to the top, with some delicate footwork (5.5) finishing just Right of thick mature pine tree (with downward-slanting branch on left side).  warning: The rock on and near this route has not been climbed much yet, and some of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber or someone setting up top anchor.  . . . (Lots of vegetation on this rock as of 2018. Be prepared when climbing to navigate around protruding trees and branches, and dealing with holds slippery with grass, lichen, moss, dirt).

name: Gertrude's Nooose
description: Some interesting moves. The concept of going over the nose makes the climb, and then thoughtful slab moves immediately above, but perhaps rest of the route does not live up to the nose part.  . . . The two pitches can be combined, but then if Top-Roping in the normal way from the bottom, using a normal dynamic rope, if the climber falls near the bottom, then due to rope stretch the fall could be longer or harder and the climber could be injured. So if trying it that way, likely better to instead use a static (or "semi-static") rope. Or at least keep the climber under tension while close to the bottom of the route.  P1: Start from left side of rock bench about 20 ft up right from big tree. Directly up slab to obvious down-protruding nose. Over nose (without using footholds on slab below right from nose) and straight up slab above, and find tree to use for belay anchor (perhaps one or both of the old light-brown peeling-bark cedar trees near the top of the dirty gully.  P2: Next aim for steeper block on right side of face. Over this and finish up vague crack to about 10 ft right from big tree stump.  warning: The rock on and near this route has not been climbed much yet, and some of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber or someone setting up top anchor.  . . . (Lots of vegetation on this rock as of 2018. Be prepared when climbing to navigate around protruding trees and branches, and dealing with holds slippery with grass, lichen, moss, dirt).  name: Gertrude's Nose is at the end of some cliffs south from Millbook Mt. Often reached by hiking/scrambling route in Minnewaska State Park. Could also be reached by first hiking south above the Near Trapps climbing sector of the Mohonk Preserve to Millbrook Mt.

name: Hamilton Pointless
description: Somewhat-thoughtful slab climbing on slanting rock in lowest part. Then gets easier less interesting. Finally just scrambling on vegetated rock.  . . . The two pitches can be combined, but then if Top-Roping in the normal way from the bottom, using a normal dynamic rope, if the climber falls near the bottom, then due to rope stretch the fall could be longer or harder and the climber could be injured. So if trying it that way, likely better to instead use a static (or "semi-static") rope. Or at least keep the climber under tension while close to the bottom of the route.  P1: Start at the base of a left-trending inside corner facing left, which is below left from obvious down-protruding nose about 25 ft up. Step up right onto left-sloping rock whiich forms high right edge of the left-facing inside corner. Up this left-sloping rock trending left, then straight up on rock along right side of gully, to pass just right of old light-brown peeling-bark cedar tree which splits low into two trunks.  P2: Up the slabs, aiming to pass right of old light-brown peeling-bark cedar tree with branches pointing downward. Also pass right of mature pine tree. Finish up grassy path to 8-inch thick peeling-bark cedar tree about 15 ft right from live tree which is just right of two low flat blocks. . . Variation: Better rock (but no protection for Leading) if just after pass by mature pine tree, instead traverse left to join finish of next route to left, roughly toward just left of live tree which is right of two low flat rocks to the right of the dead tree stump.  warning: The rock on and near this route has not been climbed much yet, and some of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber or someone setting up top anchor.  . . . (Lots of vegetation on this rock as of 2018. Be prepared when climbing to navigate around protruding trees and branches, and dealing with holds slippery with grass, lichen, moss, dirt).  name: The southern part of the land once managed by the Smiley family has an interesing lower viewpoint along a carriage road which is named Hamilton Point.

name: Over the Roof
description: Variety of fun moves, one or two a bit harder than the rest. . . . (Perhaps this route overall goes easier at 5.4 or 5.3 if choose every easier variation).  . . . The two pitches can be combined, but then if Top-Roping in the normal way from the bottom, using a normal dynamic rope, if the climber falls near the bottom, then due to rope stretch the fall could be longer or harder and the climber could be injured. So if trying it that way, likely better to instead use a static (or "semi-static") rope. Or at least keep the climber under tension while close to the bottom of the route.  P1: Start at the base of the non-tall ridge which slants down right from the big slanting roof. Up that ridge (with a steep thoughtful move early) - trending slightly left to climb onto the top of the big rock which caps the big slanting roof. . . . Variation 1a (avoids thoughtful move lower on ridge, and still fun anyway): Start in the alcove under the big roof. See two slanted protruding rocks below right from the big slanting roof rock. Climb up each of those, and join the main route up face onto top of roof rock. . . . Variation 1b (harder): Instead of joining the main route, up the left edge of the face to the top of roof rock. . . . Variation 1c (5.8-): Pull up over roof at obvious notch a bit right below from the center of the big roof rock. . . . Variation 2 (easier): From the ledge below top of big roof rock, instead of climbing face to top of roof rock,go more toward right side of that face, then turn left and partway up rock forming top of big roof. Next step right (without touching down onto dirt in between) over onto the next slabby rock, and up that to its top.  From the top of the big roof rock, step Right down into notch, then up onto next rock. Up a few feet to belay from large two-trunk tree.  P2: Next angle up Right across gentler rock to reach big left-facing inside corner just below two slanting trees at top of corner.  . . Variation: Also interesting to to traverse horizontal right across genler rock to reach the base of the big left-facing inside corner, then up along inside left side of that corner (shared with next route to right) to reach steeper "step" in the rock just below left from two slanting trees.   Up left side of tree (crux - easier if grab tree). . . Variation (also interesting): Around right side of tree.  Next up face staying just left of 4-6-inch wide crack. Finish to right side of top of face with slanting tree branch across from its right side (perhaps ducking under the branch).  warning: The rock on and near this route has not been climbed much yet, and some of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber or someone setting up top anchor.  . . . (Lots of vegetation on this rock as of 2018. Be prepared when climbing to navigate around protruding trees and branches, and dealing with holds slippery with grass, lichen, moss, dirt).

name: Portal of the Inside Way
description: Fun moves up corner, after a slab face start.  . . . The two pitches can be combined, but then if Top-Roping in the normal way from the bottom, using a normal dynamic rope, if the climber falls near the bottom, then due to rope stretch the fall could be longer or harder and the climber could be injured. So if trying it that way, likely better to instead use a static (or "semi-static") rope. Or at least keep the climber under tension while close to the bottom of the route.  P1: Start up a few feet and through the "portal" between non-large rocks, and a bit right to step up onto small block leaning against face. Then diagonal up Right between two 8-inch-thick trees, and continue up Rignt to reach bottom (or slightly above it) of left-facing inside corner which trends a bit left-ward. This corner forms the right edge of overall upper slab below the branch which slants down across top of left side of slab -- and forms the left edge of the slab down from stump of big dead fallen pine tree on top platform. , , , (This bottom-of-corner point could also be reached by lowering in on top-rope after finishing one of the other routes of this sector). . . . (or reached by climbing up to just past the "big slanting roof" rock almost to the large two-trunk tree, then traversing Right and downward).  Up that inside corner, trending left, and find a solid tree for belay anchor.  P2: Continue up left-facing corner (optional to step on two tooth rocks), later following a crack, and finishing a bit left of stump of big dead fallen pine tree on top platform.  warning: The rock on and near this route has not been climbed much yet, and some of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber or someone setting up top anchor.  . . . (Lots of vegetation on this rock as of 2018. Be prepared when climbing to navigate around protruding trees and branches, and dealing with holds slippery with grass, lichen, moss, dirt).

name: Ski Bonticou
description: Thoughtful slab climbing.  . . . The two pitches can be combined, but then if Top-Roping in the normal way from the bottom, using a normal dynamic rope, if the climber falls near the bottom, then due to rope stretch the fall could be longer or harder and the climber could be injured. So if trying it that way, likely better to instead use a static (or "semi-static") rope. Or at least keep the climber under tension while close to the bottom of the route.  P1: Up left side of ramp below the big slanting roof then up a little more easier. . . Variation 1 - "Surprising Squirm" (5.7-): Burrow up the right side of ramp, getting into the slanting "tight zone" under the big slanting roof -- using  variety of squirming techniques, and occasional handholds.  Continue up to belay from large two-trunk tree.  P2: Next traverse Right, then hike up on narrow rock slab along left side of slope to reach steeper "step" in the rock just below left from tree in left-facing corner. Up the arete on left side of "step" (about 15 ft left from left-facing corner with two angled trees) - (perhaps easier to start around left side of bottom of arete). Next trend toward center of face. Then finish to left side of top of face passing just left of slanting tree branch across from its right side.  warning: The rock on and near this route has not been climbed much yet, and some of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber or someone setting up top anchor.  . . . (Lots of vegetation on this rock as of 2018. Be prepared when climbing to navigate around protruding trees and branches, and dealing with holds slippery with grass, lichen, moss, dirt).  name? Many decades ago the Mohonk Mountain House had downhill ski trails to the north side of Mountain Rd on the southeast side of the northern Gunks ridge, a ways south from the Bonticou crag.

name: Ski Minne
description: Interesting moves at bottom, then fun easier moves higher up.  . . . The two pitches can be combined, but then if Top-Roping in the normal way from the bottom, using a normal dynamic rope, if the climber falls near the bottom, then due to rope stretch the fall could be longer or harder and the climber could be injured. So if trying it that way, likely better to instead use a static (or "semi-static") rope. Or at least keep the climber under tension while close to the bottom of the route.  P1: Start up slopy rock about five left of left end of two bench-sit rocks. Aim for just below left from large rounded rock with down-pointing prong, and so reach a distinct "step" with a jug hold at its base - (This is about 15-20 ft right and a bit downward from the bottom of the "central" left-facing inside corner). Up over the "step", using the rounded rock above right for handholds. Gets a bit tricky when the handholds stop about 10 ft up. Just before reaching the tree next to left side of the wide "ridge" up fron the down-pointing prong, turn right and get up onto top of ridge. Next goup on top of the "ridge", and find a sound tree as belay anchor. . . . Variation (easier): When reach the tree next to left side of ridge, pass on its left side and continue up the slab staying ieft of the "ridge".  P2: Continue up face and then follow a crack, finishing a bit right of the stump of big dead fallen pine tree on top platform.  warning: The rock on and near this route has not been climbed much yet, and some of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber or someone setting up top anchor.  . . . (Lots of vegetation on this rock as of 2018. Be prepared when climbing to navigate around protruding trees and branches, and dealing with holds slippery with grass, lichen, moss, dirt).  name: Ski Minne was downhill ski area with a mechanical lift, operated by the Smiley family through the southern Minnewaska mountain resort. Now in the Peterskill area of Minnewaska State Park.

name: Fifty States
description: Fun moves on interesting features.  Start at obvious left-facing inside corner about 13-15 ft uphill right from the corner arete. Up the low corner, then up the mid-way corner with crack (crux), and finish left of the upper corner with crack to finish a bit right of the jagged gnarly tree at top.  . . . Variation start: Start down left and around the corner -- up a right-trending ramp about 10 ft left of the right end of the sector Kovalcik. Up the ramp, then move Right to the obvious left-facing inside corner to rejoin main route.  warning: The rock on and near this route has not been climbed much yet, and some of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber or someone setting up top anchor.  . . . (Lots of vegetation on this rock as of 2018. Be prepared when climbing to navigate around protruding trees and branches, and dealing with holds slippery with grass, lichen, moss, dirt).

name: Laurel Ledges
description: Some thoughtful moves. Some slippery dirt/leaves. Grabbing trees is "On", but not necessarily smart or safe.  Start under obvious high big overhang on left side of cliff. Diagonal Left up steep ramp. Just before reaching gap in ramp, see dagger rock at least 2 ft long pointing down. Up R side of dagger (crux).  Next up a slippery section, then slightly Left up thru broken notch (instead of slabby right). Above notch, Finish diagonal right on slabby rock to reach gentler ground.  warning: The rock on and near this route has not been climbed much yet, and some of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber or someone setting up top anchor.  . . . (Lots of vegetation on this rock as of 2018. Be prepared when climbing to navigate around protruding trees and branches, and dealing with holds slippery with grass, lichen, moss, dirt).  FA style + Naming of routes: For more on this - - > See the Main page for Cranberry Hollow.

name: Center-Right Zig-Zag
description: Nice moves all the way. Nice as a trad Lead.  Find your way up about 25 ft to the 2-3-ft deep Left-trending diagonal crack. Next Left up this to alcove junction, then straight to the top vertical crack, perhaps finishing along R side of that top crack.  warning: The rock on and near this route has not been climbed much yet, and some of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber or someone setting up top anchor.  . . . (Lots of vegetation on this rock as of 2018. Be prepared when climbing to navigate around protruding trees and branches, and dealing with holds slippery with grass, lichen, moss, dirt).  FA style + Naming of routes: For more on this - - > See the Main page for Cranberry Hollow.

name: Dividing Gully
description: Some worthwhile moves in the bottom section. Slopy and dirty above that.  Diagonal up Left to near tree at the top of route "Li's Lunge". Next up on grass + dirt + slopy rocks + occasional tree. Finish up left to platform above left side of sector Stannard. . . . (possible harder more interesting variations to right of middle section).  warning: The rock on and near this route has not been climbed much yet, and some of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber or someone setting up top anchor.  . . . (Lots of vegetation on this rock as of 2018. Be prepared when climbing to navigate around protruding trees and branches, and dealing with holds slippery with grass, lichen, moss, dirt).  FA style + Naming of routes: For more on this - - > See the Main page for Cranberry Hollow.

name: Right Fins
description: Interesting moves (not just straight up).  Up the fins trending left (but passing rigth of bulge about 10-15 ft up). Higher up step right onto wide ramp and up that to the top platform.  warning: The rock on and near this route has not been climbed much yet, and some of the rock is still breakable and loose -- so the belayer and other people should stand far away from underneath the climber or someone setting up top anchor.  . . . (Lots of vegetation on this rock as of 2018. Be prepared when climbing to navigate around protruding trees and branches, and dealing with holds slippery with grass, lichen, moss, dirt).  FA style + Naming of routes: For more on this - - > See the Main page for Cranberry Hollow.

name: Giappo's Crack
description: Crux move is getting off the first fern-filled ledge.  Hands aren't great, you just need to trust a high, smeared foot, but the rock is so slabby and has great friction, so it's just mental.

name: Black Wall Route
description: Pitch 1: This route uses the same first pitch as ‘Valhalla’.  Pitch 2: Out of the belay follow the slanting corner on the left side of the discolored “Black Wall”. Climb through the overhanging section to another overhanging roof. Belay here. Pitch 3: Climb around the roof on its right side past a small crack to the top.  Variations: Variation 1: Shades of Death 5.8 PG/R Variation 2: Death Ledges 5.7 PG/R Variation 3: Valhalla 5.10d PG/R Variation 4: Heart of Darkness 5.10a PG/R

name: Death Ledges
description: This route starts 20 feet to the right of ‘Black Wall & Valhalla”.   Pitch 1: Climb the groove below the prow for 20 feet or so to a bulging overhang. Climb the left side up to the small belay ledge of ‘Valhalla’.  Pitch 2: From the belay, exit up and to the right toward the cave/inset. Continue up and to the left on a steep section of rock to the large overhanging roof above. Follow the black wall feature around the roof and up to the top. This section is runout but fun.

name: Easy Day for an Old Lady
description: This route starts 30 feet to the right (further uphill) from ‘Dunce’s Corner’.   Pitch 1: Climb up and to the left into a dihedral with an overhang on top. Work your way up the dihedral to the overhang and then climb left. Work your way back right past a steep rock section for about 18 feet to a belay.  Pitch 2: Follow the groove above the belay up left to the overhang. Traverse to the right around the overhang to an arete. Climb this to the top. An optional belay could be used here to avoid rope drag on the last section of the climb making it a 3-pitch route.

name: The Old Lady Climbed Well
description: Pitch 1: Climb up toward a prow following a corner system without using the left wall.  Pitch 2: Continue up toward a roof pulling past to the top.

name: Ride of the Valkyries
description: This is one of my favorite routes at the Gap!   Pitch 1: Use the same first pitch of ‘Easy Day for An Old Lady’.  Pitch 2: Exit the belay station and head to the left side of the overhang above. After the overhang go right toward the large slanted block (optional belay). From the top right side of the block climb onto the overhanging wall and continue climbing past the horizontal cracks to the top.

name: Valhalla
description: This route starts about 6 feet to the right of ‘Easy Day for An Old Lady’.   Pitch 1: Climb straight up 25 feet to a small ledge and then right toward a bulging overhang. Pull the overhang and follow the corner system up to where the wall color starts to the change (the “Black Wall” feature). Belay here.  Pitch 2: Climb up and left to a roof. Pull the roof heading int oa small dihedral. Pass a couple of small overhangs on the left side then continue climbing up toward the left side of a large overhang. Climb through to the top.

name: Cheatstone Center
description: Start at the same flak as the previous route. After a few moves toward the right to a tapered groove mid-wall. Climb the groove to the upper ledge.

name: Cheatstone Left
description: Start at the flake that sticks out on the left side of the roof. Climb the splitter crack for 2 or 3 moves then work your way up and right to the upper ledge. Henry used to warm up on this route.

name: Cheatstone Lunge
description: This route starts by standing up to the left of the top-out for the 'Standard Traverse'. Reach up and grab the lip and then grab a right facing side pull. Crank up and dyno for a small horizontal crack, then climb up to the upper ledge.

name: Cheatstone Right
description: This route starts in the two pockets on the roof near the edge. CLimb this to the top-out. THis route is the same as 'Standard Traverse'.

name: Cheatstone Traverse
description: Start on ramp under lowest end of shelter cave and undercling.  Move out left to lip of cave.  Reach to rail and use it to move to back side of cave.  From there, follow back wall to overhang on cave's upper end.  Pull this roof and proceed to top-out. (In all, about twenty or so moves to complete the problem.)

name: High Traverse
description: Climb up the corner at the left side of the block. Traverse crimpers just beneath the roof slightly go up toward the top. After you top out you can exit right.

name: Standard Traverse
description: Start at the same flake. Traverse right to an angled crimper then climb right to pull the lip at 4 pockets in the roof. Follow this to the top.

name: Warmup Traverse
description: Start in the dihedral on the right side of the block. Use several small footholds close to the ground while traversing the face to the right to the end.

name: Class Clown
description: This route starts in the same location as ‘Class Four Ramp’. At the top of the low-angle rock ramp step left to a small ledge. Traverse left for 5 to 10 feet and then up next to the arete to the top.

name: Class Four Ramp
description: This route starts 25 feet right of ‘Gymnastical Jazz’. There’s a large inset where this route starts. Scramble up the blocks to a dirt ramp and then up the low-angle rock ramp. Climb left at the top of the ramp and follow the dihedral to the top.

name: Dunce's Corner
description: This route starts 5 feet right of ‘Class Four Ramp’. Climb the left-facing arete to the top without using the wide crack on the upper section. Liebacks help up higher. This is a fun route on this wall.

name: School Teacher's Walk the Plank
description: This route follows the first lower section of the previous routes. Pitch 1: When you get to the top of the rock slab continue up to the right to a steep arete. Follow the crack on the corner to a small belay. Pitch 2: Traverse right out of the belay to the overhang. Work your way around the corner to a small ledge by a wide crack. Climb the crack up for a couple of moves and then onto the face on the left. Follow this to the top.

name: Death Don't Have No Mercy
description: The first pitch starts at the slab under the multiple roofs 30 meters above.  Climb the grassy slab in the wider crack to the right at the corner.  I built a belay under the first roof which made communication with the belayer much easier during the crux:    Climb through a series of four roofs, straight through the first roof, trending right through a moss filled crack at the second roof, straight through the third, and right at the last roof through the undercling and glorious top out.    Really grassy at the top, there may be slings and rap rings to climbers left.  Or just top out and find your way to Corkscrew rappel (double ropes).

name: Denture Grip
description: This route starts the same as ‘Indian Head’.  Pitch 1: Follow ‘Indian Head’ up for 40 feet to the left of the overhangs. Belay here. Pitch 2: Continue up the steep face following small horizontal cracks to another ledge then up to the top or belay a short section.  This route has a 5.6 and 5.9 variation of the second pitch.

name: Tomahawk
description: A great route with a first ascent from Richard Pleiss in the late 1970’s. Some people call it Tomahawk. The “Indian head” feature can be seen clearly from across the river o the Pennsylvania side of the Gap. It’s an iconic feature first noticed I the mid-1800’s by tourists on the Lackawanna Railroad. This route starts at the left-facing arete just to the right of the split tree.   Pitch 1: Climb up 15 feet and slant left continuing up another arete to a ledge. Continue up and into the dihedral with a crack to another ledge with bushes. Belay here.  Pitch 2: Exit left and traverse the ledges to the arete then up to the top.

name: Chimney Sweep
description: Start at a freindly looking low-angle face about 70' uphill of toproper's buttress.  There will be 3 medium size trees to your left, and 2 large oak trees about 20' to your right.Pitch 1: (5.3PG?) Climb easily up, trending left till you reach a crumbly looking overhang with layers of shale in it.  Head left under the overhang and around a small corner to a ledge in a notch with a slung chockstone.  Belay on the chockstone.  Rappel thru the trees or continue up.Pitch 2.  (5.5PG) Stem up the notch or go around it on the left (easier).  Head up into the chimney where an awkward overhanging exit awaits.  This will feel hard if you don't do it right.  Exit to the top and belay on some medium size trees.Descent - Hike back about 50' thru some thorny brush to gain the overcliff trail.  Follow it uphill to any of the rappels above.  When the trail comes near the cliff edge before steepening, you'll see the obvious face of The Black Wall.  There is a rappel tree just below the lip here, but I recommend continuing up another 100 feet to a 2 rope rape from the bolts on The Rib.

name: Easter Bunny
description: Climb the corner right of 'Die Hard' for about 30 to 35 feet to an overhang. Move right to another corner. Go up through the chimney, then angle left across a slab to the first left facing corner. Go up the corner, climbing a small overhang at a crack and continue up past the right end of a slab to the top.

name: Easter Egg Hunt
description: Pitch 1 (5.6)   Climb up corner passing an old pin before entering wide groove. Exit groove on left and belay at sawed off tree stump. A gear anchor is needed(#3 BD useful)   Pitch 2 (5.8)   Continue up left facing corner until stopped by roof (crux). Use crack at right of roof to awkwardly pull over into vegetated corner. Original finish (continued up left facing corner) is now full of vegetation and is not passable.    Proposed new finish move 5 feet to the left of corner and climb slabby face. Finish left of jutting roof at top. To descend walk right to 4th Class Ramp. (As of July '14 no slings) Down-climbable

name: Gallows Humor
description: Pitch 1: Same first pitch as "Chimney Sweep", except instead of passing left around the overhang climb at its center.  Pitch 2: Climb the steep wall right of the chimney.

name: Say Your Pwayers Wabbit
description: Pitch 1: Climb a short, left facing corner to a small ceiling 12 feet up. Cleat this, then continue up another 40 feet, shifting slighlty left to pass around the crumbly looking overhang above. Step right to a belay ledge below the conspicuous chimney.  Pitch 2: Traverse left, then undercling (slightly smoothed out now) and pull directly over the center of the ceiling (alternate belay here), traverse right to the center of it where you can reach over the lip for holds. Pull up to a stance, then step left and climb the next overhang at a weakness to the the top.

name: Thunderbear
description: Start at the tree on the block.   OPitch 1: Climb the left facing corner above for 15 feet to an overhang, then traverse left to another left facing corner, which is followed up to a belay ledge.   Pitch 2: Climb up a conspicuous flake, then the overhang and a slab above to the top.

name: Double Overhang
description: Right of Rad Dudes area, Left of the Great Arch Area.    Crux roof is clearly visible from the ground. Once you locate it, P1 is obvious as well.    Descend: 1 rap w/ two 60m ropes via the rib, Class 4 ramp, or corkscrew will get ya  back on the ground. You could bring a sling/ring and rap from anchor tree, however be prepared for stuck ropes and  having to walk around to the top.

name: Jungle Gym
description: Pitch 1: Start at the spot found in the picture section. Scramble up from there 20 ft. Continue up as the path described by the yellow rope found in the picture titled “Entire Pitch 1.” In a similar picture, you'll find a yellow circle, red circle, and purple arrow marking. The yellow circle marks the place where this pitch ends, a blueberry evergreen type tree. Go next to a very healthy small evergreen blueberry tree, just on its right where there is a nice ledge. This belay spot will protect you from falling rock if the leader releases blocks on the 2nd pitch. The red circle marks the crux of the pitch, where there is a small but difficult roof. The roof move is about a 5.8 DWG move…prepare to do pull ups. If the roof appears too cruxy for you, there is an escape to the left where the purple arrow is pointing to, that will allow you to skirt left and then back on top of the crux. However, beware as you come to that arete where the purple arrow is, there is some loose rock…don’t grab just anything. The picture with the yellow rope shows the line curving hard right (see the zoom picture) from the crux to get to the right of the small evergreen for a belay point, but feel free to head straight up from the crux. I thought the rock just below and left of the small evergreen looked sketchy and chose to move hard right, ending up on the right of the small evergreen. Again, this is a safer belay spot to protect you from rockfall anyway. Picture of the first belay found in the picture section. You can choose to belay just prior to the evergreen tree (just beneath) if you have #3 and #4 BD Camalots on you then. 110ft  Pitch 2: Exit left and up from the evergreen tree to some easy slab (10ft) and immediately into a large corner on your right (with a roof above to the slight left). Above you, you'll see many small trees, larger trees, and eventually a large thorn hanging bush (growing down). Don’t attempt to go on top of the formation that was above you at the belay. Instead stay in the corner, occasionally leaving the corner to the left a little to avoid loose blocks, branches, and small trees. Extend carefully to avoid rope drag. There are some very loose 50lb blocks on this route. Aim to get just to the left of the massive hanging thorn bush. Stand on top of the thorn bush (the stalks are lying flat to reach out to the sun and down). Then climb the easy 20ft chimney with stemming. Face outwards as you do this chimney. Near the top of the chimney you'll find good edges on your right (your right as you face out of the chimney) side to transition out and around onto the arete, which is 5ft out of your reach. It may seem overhanging to make this reach, but there is a nice spot for your foot on that arete once you commit out to the arete and good small fingers. One clawing onto the arete, climb about 5ft and you are at the top. 20ft back on the top there are nice slots for cams. See pic titled “2nd belay” in the pictures section. Make sure to extend from your set up back to the top edge of your climb, so that you can communicate with your follower. In this way, you'll be able to encourage struggling followers as they move from chimney to arete. 100ft  Like 75% of the lcimbs in the DWG, make sure to bring working cell phones or two-way radios. It is impossible to hear well at times with I-80 road traffic, wind, etc.

name: Outside Chance
description: This route has the same start as ‘Double Overhang’.   Pitch 1: Climb up the groove for 15 feet and work your way right for 10 feet. Continue up the face here and step left to a small belay.  Pitch 2: Exit right and up the prow. Stay to the right and toward the left edge of the large overhang. Climb the obvious angled crack to meet up with the previous route. Belay here.  Pitch 3: Exit up and climb the arete to the upper overhang. Traverse far right (sketchy but fun) underneath the narrow roof to the far end and then up small holds o the arete to the top.

name: Sobriety Test
description: This route has the same start as ‘Jungle Gym’.   Pitch 1: Climb up to the triangle shaped roof dihedral passing it on the right. You can belay just below the upper roof.  Pitch 2: Exit right around the roof then climb left toward the prow. Pass the first overhang left then back right after the second overhang. Continue up past the horizontal cracks to the top.

name: Triple Overhang
description: This route starts 30 feet right of ‘Spanning the Gap’.   Pitch 1: Start climbing the arete up to the roof. Pull the roof on the right side using a thin crack and jugs and then over the next roof using an obvious crack. Continue climbing until you reach the small belay ledge.  Pitch 2:  Exit up and climb past a small block system, several horizontals and up to the tope of the cliff.

name: Colorado
description: This route has alot of bad rock on it.  Not for a novice!  This is particularly true on the middle of the route where the often black rock is hollow sounding and will not hold a real fall.  Consider it very dangerous overall.  Work hard to find solid rock placements, which are sometimes few and far between.  Pitch 1 (5.6+): Climb the corner that is just before the tree (in picture by Joe Heinz) at the base, passing the ceiling on it's right. Your initial goal is to stand on top of that ceiling. Turning to pass the ceiling is a crux move.....look for a hand jam in this move to help you (see Joe Heinz's pic with yellow circle highlight).  At crux, there is a large loose rock on your right...be careful not to grab.  The crux move might be much higher than 5.6.  My partner and I felt it was more towards a 5.8 at the DWG. After passing the roof, climb up to the easy access ledge, which has many thorns, and belay (see pic). 40ft  LINK Pitch 2 and 3 together: Pass the small roof that is just above the belay station by directly going up through the roof or by stepping 5ft to the right and accessing the easier arete and face.  This small roof is 10-15ft above the belay station. Climb up to the corner directly above 2nd roof and follow it until huge overhangs force you hard left and out to the obvious arete to your left that turns 90 degrees and places you on a new face. This is easy climbing in this section (5.4).  The rock in this corner and as you escape the roof at the very top of the climb (according to the old description pitch 2) is often bad, and no good belay can now be created at the 90 deg turn from the one face to the other.   Once you make this 90deg turn, you'll be out from underneath the large roof that was above you (for the old description of pitch 2) and find a new corner to climb with no roof above you. From above 2nd small roof to 90 deg turn is 85ft. Continue up now in the new obvious corner.  Pass the 2 trees very near the top (found in my other pic) because they have become suspect raps to the more solid rock at the top out to make an anchor.  It would be better to top out and walk your way back over to the triumvirate face and rap down off of THE RIB route. The 2nd corner section is about 80ft long.  To make the above run, since the rock is pretty questionable along the 2nd and 3rd pitch with no clear anchor point, you need to link together pitch 2 and 3.  To accomplish that, every piece needs an extended alpine runner.  I suggest a 70m rope.  (2nd and 3rd pitch together could be from 180ft to 200ft depending on your angle you take to escape the huge roof on the 2nd pitch)  I may have missed the belay station the 90deg turn mentioned above...but I searched hard for it and could not find it.  It may have collapsed out.  All I found was alot of nominal placements in nominal rock....alot of hollow sounding, black rock.  If you can find it, please take a pic and rewrite the above description.  I would love to have that 2nd belay station and not create a link up of 2 pitches.

name: Corner Cap
description: This route starts 5 feet to the right of ‘Eldorado’ in the dihedral. Climb up the dihedral and around the right side of the overhang above to the ledge. Walk off descent.

name: Eldorado
description: This is a short, but fun route! It starts 23 feet right of ‘Buddha’s Delight’ and just left of a dihedral (Corner Cap). Start on the thin crack up for 20 feet to a notched overhang. Climb over the notch for 10 feet to the ledge. Walk-off descent from the ledge back to the trail.

name: Last Call
description: This route starts 6 feet right of ‘Quivering Hips’. Climb the obvious crack for 25 feet to the ledge. Walk off descent.

name: Old Smoothie
description: This route starts 20 feet right of ‘Last Call’ on the easy access ramp. Climb over the overhang onto the wall above. Climb left and up at the small arete onto the ledge.

name: Quivering Hips
description: This route starts 15 feet to the right of ‘Rad Dudes from Hell’. Climb the crack through the overhang then another 15 feet to a small tree on a ledge. This is a popular top-rope route or short lead. If lead you must lower off the tree.

name: Spanning the Gap
description: This route starts on the previously mentioned ledge below a large left-facing arete.   Pitch 1: Climb up the large arete until you reach the overhangs.Traverse right along the mid-sized horizontal crack passing several old rusty pitons (1 left out of 6 original placed by Nicholas Clifford and the Princeton Mountaineering Club in the early 1950’s). Eventually you’ll reach a small ledge. Belay here.  Pitch 2: Exit up passing larges bulges to a dihedral to the top.

name: That Was Zen, This is Tao
description: This route starts on the ledge above ‘Buddha’s Delight’.   Pitch 1: Start on the ledge and climb through the overhang via a crack. Continue climbing up and to the left toward a left-facing dihedral. Climb the outside/arete of it to the top of it. Move right around the arete up top and then up to the ledge.  Pitch 2: The second pitch is the same as ‘Colorados’ second pitch.

name: Buddha's Delight
description: Start on the small ledge and climb up the left-facing dihedral crack about 15 to 20 feet until you reach a notch/small chimney with a ledge above it. Climb to ledge and walk-off. This route is sometimes done as a first pitch variation to ‘That Was Zen, This is Tao’.

name: Friends in High Places
description: With intensive cleaning or more traffic this could be a worthwile route, thought it is currently overgrown with small trees, poison ivy, and loose rock.  Hit it in the early spring before the foliage comes in.    Starting on the slab next to the open book that begins the rib, move up a groove to a small roof atop the slab.  Pull this on the right end, then pull up the larger roof at the middle on obvious jugs (well protected, but last decent gear for a bit).  Continue up until you reach a grassy ledge.  Belay on 1-1/2" gear at the left end of the ledge.    P2 - Climb up the corner above the belay, then head hard right, fighting Poison Ivy and a birch tree, then move up onto the soft sloping dirt ledge (Loose rocks!), and weave thru the small trees to 20' of gorgeous crack (reminiscent of CCK at the Gunks) At the end of the crack, move left, avoiding a stack of loose-looking blocks and a tree, then up to the top.  Belay on small gear or trees.    Descend via The Rib with 2 single rope rappels or 1 double rope rappel.    Rope drag on P2 could be pretty bad with the way the route wanders.  For an alternative, Continue P1 straight up from the belay ledge (looks unprotected), and do a semi-hanging belay below P2.

name: Ghetto Superstar
description: Going by the route name, apparently Matt Hill and Mark Ronca were feeling like superstars during their first ascent of this route in the 90’s. This is a fun variation of a route but I separated it for FA purposes. This route starts toward the top of ‘Friends in High Places’. It has been called “The Dangler” of the Gap. Traverse right along the upper roof. Toward the edge of the roof, climb right and up the slab to the top.

name: Ribbed Pleasures
description: This route starts 10 feet right of ‘The Rib’.   Pitch 1: Start on the lower slab and up to the overhangs. Staying right of the upper arete, continue climbing up to a ledge with a tree on it. Belay here.  Pitch 2: Exit belay ledge to the left around an arete and climb the face to a bolt. Continue climbing the steep face into horizontal off-width cracks. Traverse to the right and climb up past another bolt and into a dihedral under a roof. Pull the roof on the right climb up past the crux to the top.   Mark Ronca placed these bolts during the first ascent in the 90’s.

name: Zen Corner
description: This route has the same start location as ‘Friends in High Places’. Start on the steep slab toward the left-facing arete. Climb left across the upper part of the slab and over several bulges to reach another overgrown arete. Join up with ‘Friends in High Places’ for the finish. Another cool Mike Steele first ascent.

name: Chipped Tooth Crack
description: This was a good climb but very dirty with Foliage and brush at this time of year. I did this December 7th, so its probably better in spring or summer. Has a decent traverse to the right, so make sure you bring plenty of protection. To get to the start, Walk the base line past the Rib, up around the next bend and look for the large wedge. A few trees at the base.  Historic Note: The story behind this route from Doug Greene (who was watching Hugh and Henry climb it in 1975. All 3 were guides here in the 1970's). Hugh had place a piton and couldn't get it out. After several hits wit ha hammer and tugs it popped out and smacked him in the mouth chipping his tooth.

name: The Chute
description: This route starts 10 feet to the right further uphill from ‘Sunday Special’.   Pitch 1: Climb the arete and onto the middle of the face to a belay at a tree.  Pitch 2: Exit up and climb the smooth arete o the right side of the roof. Continue climbing past horizontals and a small overhang to the top.

name: corkscrew
description: Corkscrew is a great route. The rock on top of the second pitch is high quality for the gap. Some punchy overhang moves on P1; P2 has a scary PG13/R corner off the belay, an indimidating traverse, and some overhang moves to a top out similar to Modern Times.  Scramble up 15 feet off the trail to a ledge with some trees to start.  P1. Climb a slab to a left facing corner that starts at the left end of a low roof. Climb straight up the corner, plug your gear, and pull the overhanging moves above, exiting right (crux) to a belay.  P2. Climb up the corner above on very thin gear, exit right (Mental crux, scary, great gear just after the scary part) just below the ceiling. Continue up easier ground for a bit and find a good belay.  P3.  Head right below and thru a series of roofs (Fixed pin far right), topping out at a distinct step in the last roof (second crux, well protected).  Belay at a set of rappel bolts and a stout cedar tree.

name: Godzilla
description: shares a start with Tree Toad Fracture. Rides the arete with crazy exposure with nothing but air and I-80 at your back. Guide book lists 4 bolts, but I only saw three as I rap'd past the climb. Falls past the second bolt looked clean, you would have to climb Tree Toad to set up an epic TR on the first pitch or to hang draws and work the line.

name: Martin's Fall
description: P1. Start up some easy terrain, passing a bulge/small roof on the right and heading up to a second, larger roof, with two knifeblade pitons (Optional belay). Pass the roof on the left, Then make your way right to the corner at the top of a short slab under another large roof (slightly difficult route finding & gear). Semi-hanging belay here on medium-small gear.  For a better variant, climb P1 of Tree Toad Fracture.  The routes share the belay at the end of P1, doesn't change the grade, and protects well after the initial 5.easy runout to the corner.  P2. Move up the steep corner on good holds and good gear. Once esablished under the next (largest) roof, traverse left around the point (Note 1) and belay at the Corkscrew Cedar.  Gear is sufficient, but not plentiful.  Note 1 - there are two things to be concerned with at the point.  The upper large horizontal crack and the lower half inch horizontal crack... the rope will likely want to run thru one of them, it won't get stuck, but the edges are sharp.  Careful gear extension will  keep the rope out.  Descend via double rope rap from the 2 bolts atop corkscrew.  Very airy rappel.

name: Sunday Special
description: This route starts the same as ‘Corkscrew’.   Pitch 1: Climb up about 20 feet along the arete. Head right and follow the left edge of the low angle rock where it meets the steep wall. Traverse far right along the joining edge of low and steep rock. Continue traversing to the corner and then up to a ledge with a cedar tree on it. Belay here.  Pitch 2: Exit left traversing the ledge to a left-facing arete and then straight up to the top. This route has a 5.4 variation called ‘Sunday Plus’ that starts 10 feet right of this route, follows up the face and then rejoins it. Cool variation!

name: Tree Toad Fracture
description: First pitch is a dirty right facing open book. The pitch has gear where you need it, but by no means plentiful. The pitch finishes in a very cramped belay dike/ledge after some fun moves. The second pitch goes up to the obvious roof above, with no true rest.  The roof is then exited by traversing 15ft right on underclings and smears/small feet and then up to a pair of bolts in good condition and rap rings. BE WARNED, if the second blows it during the roof section there is no easy way of getting back on the wall as they will be left dangling in space with 80ft of clean air below them.  Also worth noting, the gear directly above to belay on pitch 2 is pg13/R for about ten feet and a slip here would be bad news. Additionaly if the leader goes for a ride during the roof section, with rope stretch and swing they could easily drop kick the belayer. For a bonus third pitch you can top out and wander back to the corkscrew rap station on your left, or stay roped up and make your way to the climbers left over some grassy ledges with no protection to the same station.

name: Trick Photography (Alt 1)
description: Great Arch Area. Starts just inside of the corner to the right of the wall.  Can scramble up about 35 to 40 feet before starting, there is a decent ledge to belay from just above a small tree. Pitch #1:  Heading for straight above, have to work left and right about 70 feet till under a ceiling. you will have to pass a small tree with a red cordelette and D link. **(Alt ) to complete the route must go right, I went left and made my way onto Outside Chance. Pitch #2 Traverse left about 40 feet  and ascend up  50 feet and make your way for second spot for Belay station under a big ceiling. Pitch#3, Work up and to the left till just under the ceiling at another outside corner, now a long traverse left following just under the ceiling until reaching a sharp corner which you must climb up to make your way up to the top. (Look at the Photo's, they should be very helpful. I made a climb next to the route to add additional views of the climb. )

name: Free Trial
description: This route starts 10 feet right of the ‘Great Briar Roof’. Climb up the middle of the long, horizontal roof on the thing crack that widens toward the edge of the roof.

name: Six Year Itch
description: 30 feet downhill from the ‘Great Briar Roof’ is another roof at the same height.   Pitch 1: Climb up a left-facing arete toward a crack in the upper roof.
