Work your way toward the chimney. Belay here.  Pitch 2: Exit up and into the chimney then a finger jam crack out of the roof. Continue up the slab above to a large cedar tree. Rappel here.

name: Decent Exposure
description: Same start as ‘Easy Lieback’.   Pitch 1: Climb up from the tree to the right on the ledges just right of the arete. Climb up and right of the arete about 60 feet to a prow and white face. Climb left into a dihedral above another face and up to a ledge. Belay here.  Pitch 2: Traverse right 35 to 45 feet to a rappel tree.

name: Easy Lieback
description: Scramble up to the start ledge just below the large, left-facing arete at a tree. Starting 10 feet left of the tree, climb the blank slab up. Continue up and over an overhang joining with the main arete again 75 feet off the ledge. At the top of the arete work your way left to the ledge. From the left-side of the ledges climb up and left to the top.

name: Liquid Squeeze
description: Same start as ‘Easy Lieback’. From the tree climb up a groove to a roof. Pass over the roof and into the dihedral above it. Climb right and into a small chimney then up several cracks to the upper roof and then to the top.

name: Outlander
description: This route starts 30 feet to the right of “Decent Exposure’. Climb up the dihedral, left-facing arete past an overhang system and several smaller overhangs to the rappel tree.

name: Sharks Fin
description: At the top of 'Easy Lieback' head to the right side of the obvious fin at the top of the cliff. Climb through a steep groove, then hand traverse the fin left, sling the fin's tip and make a difficult mantle to the top.

name: Crack in the Forest
description: This route starts 45 feet to the right of ‘Wilderness of Decay’.   Pitch 1: Climb up the sketchy, blocked tiers to a cedar tree below a roof on a ledge. Belay here.  Pitch 2: Exit up and right through the overhanging system to a finger crack. Continue up the crack as it widens at the edge up to the top.

name: Final Impact
description: Another great Mark Ronca route from 1998! Well worth the hike up to it. This route starts 5 feet to the right of ‘Crack in the Forest’. Climb the roof via the thin crack. Continue past the roof through another roof using small gear up to the top.

name: Overhangs Ah'Coming
description: Start at the base of the chossy arete. Follow the arete up for 30 feet and work your way over the overhangs to another small roof system. Topping out at a tree rappel.

name: Pray for Death
description: Climb up the arete on the right side of the slab for 90 to 100 feet. Traverse out left onto a ledge to several trees. Rappel here. Short single-pitch route but fun.

name: Wilderness Decay
description: This route starts 10 feet to the right of ‘Pray for Death’. Start by climbing up the left-facing dihedrals through a smaller overhang system. Look for a discolored, orange overhang above. Work toward that. Climb up and into the corner passing the roof toward the right. Rappel off the trees on the right side (same rappel tree for 'Overhangs Ah'Coming').

name: Another Roadside Attraction
description: Pitch 1 (5.6)   10 feet right of the Dead Man's Curve crack   Climb crack in left facing corner to belay block.    Pitch 2 (5.7)   Off belay block pass first prow on the right hand side. Continue up over second prow at its left until met with an overhang. Hand traverse moving left ~8 feet to small ledge. Up short slab at top belaying in horizontals. To descend this climb scramble or continuing leading right to grassy area. The rappel is found 80 feet to the right at large chock stone the top of JG/The Chiseler. A 70m rope reaches the ground with plenty extra. A 60m should get you to a safe point to down climb, please knot your ends.

name: Dead Man's Curve
description: Up slab following crack that moves to the right. Traverse crack right until it is possible to move straight up on top of ledge. Belay at slung block. (slings replaced July 16, 2014)   Optional second pitch see Another Roadside Attraction

name: Highway to Hell
description: Cruise up the left side of inset past small maple and corner to grassy ledge. Up and a step right past some semi-secure rock, and on up to the top hang. Fingery holds lead over the hang at a small horn which is visible from below. Tricky protection at the crux. Caution advised.     Cold at the floor but gets warmer on your way up. Lots of Brush and Foliage in the fall makes it messy.     Highway to hell

name: JG/The Chiseler
description: This route was named after John Greene, who supposedly chiseled his name in the rock. John Greene was one of the first climbing guides in the DWG in the 1970’s along with Hugh Dougher. He was also the brother of the owner of Packshack Adventures, the first guide service in the DWG. This route starts 12 feet to the right of ‘Lie Detector’. Start at the initials on a small chimney feature working your way up the face onto ta small ledge. Go right about 5 feet and continue up the face following a small crack/groove. Go toward the left underneath and around a large triangular shaped overhang to the top.

name: Premature Exasperation
description: The small roof just right of JG's chimney. Climb straight up to the tier and good horizontal below the small roof. Straight over this to a thin seam (small nut) in a slab. Up the slab past slopers to big horizontal (3-4in gear).     The Falcon guide lists a second pitch (not in the Steele guide), that looked grungy and overgrown. A better option is to traverse the horizontal left, joining JG at the groove.     Easily top roped by climbing JG's chimney and traversing right, or by scrambling up the weakness 20ft. to the right of the route.

name: Tammany Girdle (Incomplete)
description: When climbing at the Delaware Water Gap is mentioned, most people describe the style of climbing as "Adventure Climbing" due to the moss covered and vegetated nature of the rock, and the limited climbing traffic the majority of the cliff receives.  With that being said, if you are looking for some long adventure climbing, the Tammany Girdle will absolutely fit the bill.    I'll point out here we did our best to follow the guidebook description, which is laughably vague for such a long route, so if we did not follow the "true" girdle route line, it was because we honestly had no idea where we were going.    Per the Falcon Guide "Rock Climbing New Jersey" "Tammany Girdle (5.7) Traverse the middle of the cliff from I-80 to Easy Lieback in many pitches.  At the Colorado route, temporarily descend enough to bypass the bleak, dark wall."    So I'll try to further clarify the above description with our chosen route:   Pitch 1: Start on Dead Man's Curve and climb the entire pitch.  At the fixed anchor, continue climbing right under a low roof until a V notch is reached.  Climb to the top of the notch and belay at a stance.  5.8+ 150ft.   Pitch 2: Climb right from the belay and follow the grassy ledges which angle up and right at approximately 1/3 cliff height.  Belay on a grassy ledge with a fixed sling after approximately 150ft. 5.1   Pitch 3: Climb right on easy ~5.6 terrain up a slabby ramp and continue climbing right.  Near the end of the pitch, climb across a chimney and belay at a stance with some old fixed slings.  5.7 150 ft   Pitch 4: Climb right off the belay to the inside corner, and down climb the corner approximately 6 feet, then move right and around the outside corner and continue climbing right and slightly up.  Belay at the outside corner near the Class Four Ramp Area.  5.8 PG 13 150ft.   Pitch 5: Climb right across the Class Four Ramp to the steeper wall with diagonaling cracks, utilizing the cracks pull around onto the slabby ramp and continue up and right to the belay at the end of Black Wall pitch 1.  5.8 100ft.   Pitch 6: Climb the inside corner pitch of Black Wall, and continue right past the tree below the ceiling and across the easy face ending at the top of Triumvirate.  5.7 100ft.   Pitch 7: Traverse right off the belay and follow the wide crack to The Rib, follow the corner to the top of the wall and the P2 bolts.  5.3 50ft.   Rappel The Rib until you reach the slabby ramp below Friends in High Places at about 50ft off the ground.   Pitch 8: We fought thru some trees under "spanning the gap", and then started diagonaling up the wall, eventually joining the first pitch of Double Overhang, ending on a steeply angled ledge at the outside corner about 15 feet above the Mid-wall juniper on Double Overhang. (Very awkward belay, but the best spot for the traverse - 15 feet left of and 6 feet above the Corkscrew Belay)    Pitch 9: From the P8 belay, it is only about 15 feet to the Corkscrew first station belay. Passing the corkscrew belay and continuing around the arete, we continued across, passing Martin's Fall with very thin gear (Brassies / Ballnuts), and continuing just past Tree Toad Fracture on the slabs (RT#67 in the Falcon Guide). This section is dangerous for the second. The last 20 feet to the inside corner tenuous and unprotected at about 5.8 if you find the holds.    Pitch 10: From P9 it was easy traversing up slabs with occasional fights with trees. Belayed on the slabs about 120 feet at a spot about 20' below a large tree with slings and rings.     The angle after of the cliff is dramatically reduced, I think the remaining traversing pitches would be relatively easy.   Pitch 11: Here, we topped out - was good climbing till the last 20 feet, which were loose with a loose and steep topout. I don't recommend repeating the top out.

name: Crayola Crack
description: Start by climbing up the far-left side of the slab and up through the double cracks above. Traverse right to a rappel pine tree.

name: Lost Jersey Boys
description: This route starts 12 feet right of ‘Real World’. Follow the black slab through the tiered roof system above working your way right past a horizontal crack. Traverse right to the rappel tree.

name: Real World
description: This route starts 10 feet right of ‘Crayola Crack’. Climb the blank slabt o the large roof by the right-facing dihedral. Traverse right to the rappel pine.

name: Short Circuit
description: This route starts 8 feet right of ‘Real World’. Climb the slab up to the right-facing dihedral I the roof. Same traverse to the right to a rappel tree.

name: Sunshine
description: Climb up the thin, vertical crack o the right side of the lower slab toward the double cracks in the roof above. Climb left to the rappel tree.

name: Toy Box
description: 60 right of ‘Sunshine’ is another great route that starts at a roof with a thin crack in a roof above. Climb the lower slab to a right-facing arete. Once your reach the roof traverse right along the large block. Climb the thin finger crack to a rappel cedar.

name: Four Play
description: Climb the blocky, left facing corner that forms the left end of the buttress. Follow weaknesses up and slightly left to a large ceiling. Traverse left then up through the "V" between the huge overhangs.

name: Little Shop of Horrors
description: Pitch 1: Climb the thin crack through the center of the low ceiling (at the tree), then up the face to the ledge and tree belay.   Pitch 2: Continue up a corner to another ledge, then past some junky rock to gain a chimney-like groove. Exit left (crux) at the top of this to a rappel station.

name: Scrabble
description: Same start as 'Squeezebox'. Immediately angle right and up to the left facing corner left of the big overhanging prow near the top.

name: Squeezebox
description: Start at a 12 foot high right facing corner just right of the right end of the protruding buttress. Climb this corner, then move up and slightly left through a series of narrow slots to the top.

name: Gymnastical Jazz
description: Start 30 feet right of previous routes, at a short crack that starts 6 feet up and slants leftward. Climb the crack and weaknesses above to the big, pointed ceiling near the top. Climb this ceiling on the right at a crack.

name: The Hangman
description: Pitch 1: Climb easy rock up and left to a belay at a bush below the Trapdoor Chimney.   Pitch 2: Step up left and climb the crux ceiling at an obvious crack, then up to the top or the rappel tree.

name: Trapdoor Chimney
description: Begin just right of 2 large Oak trees, about 100 feet up hill from top-roper's buttress.Pitch 1. Head up fairly easy terrain to a face with very little gear.  Pass this at a large crack on the right, and continue up to a small overhang with some birch trees on the left.  Grunt past the overhang on the left to a sloping ledge beneath the chimney. (or belay here and go around right?)Pitch 2: Follow the line of least resistance through the chimney to the rappel tree.  This pitch appears to have many questionable and loose looking stacked blocks.

name: Trapeze
description: Pitch 1: Climb straight up to a slab that is even with and about 20 feet right of the bush belay for the previous routes.   Pitch 2: Move back right to the top of the slab, then traverse right below overhangs until you can clear them on their right.

name: Water Gap Waltz
description: Pitch 1: Start just to the right of 'Gymnastical Jazz". Climb up the face wit ha crack to your left to the roof.  Pitch 2: Continue past the roof up the slope to the top.

name: Cryptic Chimney
description: Start at the base to the left of the big block with the tree on top.   Pitch 1: Climb straight up past the vegetated ledges to the face. Through the left-facing corners to the chimney above. Belay here.  Pitch 2: Climb up and into the crux chimney to the top. Belay and rappel form the trees or bolts on the far right.

name: Dead Climber's Society
description: Pitch 1: Start in the dihedral at the base of the block and to the right of ‘Triumverate’. Climb up the short dihedral onto the face past the ledge and work your way over into the upper dihedral. Stay in the corner for about 35 to 40 feet and then climb left just below the overhang. Belay here.  Pitch 2: Climb up over the overhang (a 4 foot sling works well here to avoid rope drag) and onto the upper angled face. Continue past 2 horizontal cracks to the top. Belay and rappel from the trees or bolts on the far right side.

name: The Rib
description: Start at the right side base of the big block below the dihedral. (This route can be done in one pitch wit ha 70 meter rope).   Pitch 1: Climb up the dihedral and work your way left onto a ledge just below a small face. Work your way up the face where there’s lots of anchors placements to a large ledge with 2 bolts about 3 feet off the ledge. Belay here.  Pitch 2: Climb straight up the upper face into the dihedral staying left to the top. Belay and rappel from the trees or bolts on top of the cliff.

name: Ribby Bulge
description: The large block at the base of 'The Rib' offers several boulder problems. One specific faces the river on the West side. Climb the face toward the top of the bulge. Best top-roped as a fall with result in sliding down the hill.

name: Shadow Line
description: (Previously rated a 5.5 but upgraded to a 5.6) – This route has some great exposure so be cautious.   Pitch 1: Start at the base where ‘Tanemund’ and ‘Triumverate’ start. Climb up and to the left past the small overgrown ledges to the leftmost prow passing over an overhang. Pass several overhangs and a small face with plenty of jugs if you look around. Climb to the small ledge, belay here. Pitch 2: Climb to an overhang and follow the large crack on the left to the top. Belay and rappel from the trees or walk to the ‘The Rib’ rappel bolts.

name: Tanemund
description: Named after a legendary chief of the Lenni Lenape. This is a classic trad route at the Gap!  Pitch 1: Start at the base about 8 feet left of the big block with the tree on top. Climb over the vegetated sections to the blocked wall above. Climb up and left moving out onto a small face with an overhang below you. Climb up this face past the horizontal cracks onto another face up to a belay ledge with an old piton o the left. Pitch 2: Climb up and left onto a small arete to the upper face staying left to the top. Belay and rappel from trees on top.

name: Triumverate
description: The second most popular route at Mt Tammany, with several variations.  Start 4 feet left of the big block with the tree on top of it.   Pitch 1: Climb up over the vegetated ledges to the blocky wall above. Climb toward a short chimney, through the chimney and then work your way right to a small ledge. Belay here. There’s a vertical crack 5 feet off the ledge for anchors.  Pitch 2: Traverse far left about 15 to 20 feet across the horizontal cracks and then climb up the face to the top. This is the most photographed section of a climb at the Delaware Water Gap. Belay and rappel from the trees on top.  Noteable Variations:  Triumvirate Direct - From mid-way up P2 as described, head left to gain an obvious large left facing corner and slabby face (potentially move the belay or end P1 here).  Follow this up till meeting a roof at the very end of the P3 traverse.  Place good gear and make an airy and committing swing around onto the face above the roof, rejoining P3 just below the cedar tree.  5.6.  Descent:  A 180' double rope rappel from a bolted anchor, or continue 20' up 5.0 terrain to the very top.

name: A Time for Action
description: 35 feet to the left of 'Headstone'.   Pitch 1: Scramble up to the highest tree on a lsanting ledge. Climb the orangish corner right of the tree for about 15 feet until you can step left an dgain the leftmost of two parellel cracks. Move up to a horizontal crack, which allows you to gain the rightmost crack. Move right to climb the center of a ceiling at a corner crack. Continue to the same ledge as 'Route 209'.  Pitch 2: Follow the ledge to the right and up follow a seam and small blocks to the top.

name: Headhunter
description: Start just left of a row of trees in a gulley. Head up 15 feet past the row of trees to a fairly small ledge that slants downward. Climb a small corner, then straight up rock over slight overlaps. Near the top, climb a last overlap past some loose looking rock with a slight corner above. Emerge onto a ledge with a big block. At a lower angle, continue to a cedar tree at the top for a two rope rappel.

name: Route 209
description: Start at a tree 35 feet from 'A Time for Action'.  Pitch 1: Climb straight up from the tree, passing short corners and gain the left end of a slanted ledge high up on a cliff.  Pitch 2: Follow the ledge right and up almost to the end, then continue straight up to the top.

name: Do or Fly
description: Climb over low angle terrain into a belay alcove just below a roof system. From the alcove,, move out left and up to another alcove, then leap through the steep tiers and onto the top. Double rope rappel.

name: Dreams of Jessica
description: Pitch 1: Climb the face 5 feet right of 'Do or Fly' heading for the right side of the large ceiling and belay.  Pitch 2: Climb through the roof at a thin seam making a strenuous move at the lip.

name: Crocodile Tears
description: This route starts 2 feet to the right of ‘Slammer Jam’. Climb up through a notch then up the quartz veined roof system to the top.

name: Medicine Man
description: There used to be a large uprooted tree signifying this route but its since rotted away. Look for the white buttress. This route starts 10 feet to the left of that feature. Climb up the blocky corners then onto a tiered slab below a roof. Pull the crux roof on the left of the narrow section then up right onto the slabs to the top.

name: Roadcut Surprise
description: Pitch 1: Climb the same first pitch as 'Slacker's Ceiling'  Pitch 2: 5 feet right of the roof is another roof with a finger crack. Climb the roof then up the finger crack then head up and right to a belay at a tree.

name: Screams Unheard
description: This is a variation of the previous route but fun!   Pitch 1: Same first portion of the first pitch as ‘Slacker’s Ceiling’ but climb the thin upper seam through the overhanging roof and onto the slab then up the belay.  Pitch 2: Same as previous route.

name: Slacker's Ceiling
description: This route starts 20 feet right of ‘Warpath’.   Pitch 1: Climb up the sketchy rock to a belay ledge just below a roof. Belay here.  Pitch 2: Exit up through the crux overhanging roof and then up the face to the top.

name: Slammer Jam
description: Look for the large white buttress with several roof systems on it. Start by climbing the left-facing arete wit ha roof at its top. Continue climbing up in the small dihedral and up to the top.

name: Warpath
description: This route starts 40 feet right of ‘medicine Man’.   Pitch 1: Climb up the blocky corner system into a tiered section of overlapping rock to a stance. Belay here.  Pitch 2: Exit left and up toward the large roof at the widest section below a hanging corner. Climb into the overhang reaching left for a hidden hold. Work your way left and into a hanging dihedral. Continue climb up over the next overhang capping what’s below. Continue up the slabs above to the top.

name: Forces of Pfurry
description: Mark Ronca named this route after his first ascent partner on it, David Pfurr. David took one of the  Allamuchy pics of the ‘Lead Wall’ in this book. Same start as ‘Zombie’.   Pitch 1: Follow the previous routes ramp up to a horizontal crack on a left-facing wall. Traverse out on the crack right and then around an arete. Climb up the face then work right and belay from there.  Pitch 2: Exit up and climb the arete and out onto the crux roof. Continue up and into the dihedral to the top.

name: Tequila Morning
description: This route follows the same first pitch as ‘Forces of Pfurry’. From the belay climb up and right to a blank roof about 10 feet to the right of the crux in the roof. Continue up the overhangs to the top.

name: Zombie
description: This route starts by the pine tree on the ledge above the trail. Climb up the arete just left of a buttress to a small tree. Rappel here.

name: Zombie Ranger
description: This route follows the previous route for 40 feet. When you reach a dihedral, follow that up and left onto the upper section of the previous route. More of a variation to the previous route but fun.

name: Blairstown Crack
description: 10 ' to the right of Priceton crack . It's the center ( wide ) crack on the main buttress . Starts out easy with the hard move after the crack . There are two 5.10 variations at the top .

name: Free Radical
description: This route is just a short variation to 'Blairstown Crack'. Climb the thin face just right of the crack. A serious of small crimpers and dimples with steady feet and you'll bag the cruz ;)

name: Jason's Crack
description: This route climbs the right of center crack system on the main wall.  Start directly below the crack and head straight up.  The crux is down low and gear is tricky there, but the gear improves greatly once you gain the crack.  For an easier and safer start you can drop the grade by romping up the ramp to the right, and then traversing left to gain the base of crack system.

name: Mr. Mantis the Podiatrist
description: Great Route for the area! Start to the left and around the corner from Proboscis. The first part of the climb follows a thing crack left of the prominent arrete/nose. Continue up past a bulge until you reach the base of the nose jetting out of the cliff (crux). Once you reach the ceiling, climb the airy traverse left to an opening, then up to the top where three trees can be used as anchors.

name: One Bowl Ceiling
description: A one-move 5.8, just to the right of One Bowl Gully. There are a couple of small overhangs to fool around on. Begin just to the right of the low-angle groove, head up to a right-facing corner in the ceiling near the top of the cliff. Climb the ceiling at the corner.    There are lots of variations that you can play with here, and along with the natural protection, there are at least two newly placed bolts at the top of the route. Be careful about placement of your master point here, as you'll need it to hang down quite a bit off of the cliff edge.

name: One Bowl Gully
description: Great route for the first time leader . Sucks up gear everywhere and an easy top anchor set up with nice belay stance ( sitting ) . Probably worth another star or two for beginners . Follow the gully up and to the right . 20 ' left of the main buttress .

name: Princeton Crack
description: 10' to the left of Blairstown Crack . It's the skinny crack at the left end of the buttress . I finished it off near the arete .

name: Proboscis
description: Climb directly up the arete, proceed past the nose then pass through the easiest weakness in the overhang above.

name: Roof crack
description: Thin roof crack left of Mr. Mantis. Very dirty. Climb up easy slab to the roof. Plug some thin gear and then go for it! Short but awesome sequence. Easy climbing after the roof to the top. Decent is a pain. Good cedar to rap from right of top out.

name: Chrissy's Bowl
description: Start at the base of the right side of the wall below a slight bowl feature in the rock. Follow this up to the first ledge below a boulder stack. Negotiate the boulders and follow to the top.

name: High Point Face
description: Start at a large boulder protruding from the ground. Follow small cracks and crimpers to the ledge with flakes balanced on them. Continue onto the face above the flakes to the top.

name: Joey Ate Lichen
description: Start at the right most crack on the wall and follow to the boulder ledge. Follow to upper ledge  (crux) to the top.

name: Micky's Run
description: Start just right of the left-most arete below the double ledge. Follow the face up to a small ledge, past a flake system then to the top.

name: Monumental Scramble
description: Start on left most arete and follow the thin line crack up the wall to two horizontal flared cracks. The cracks are usually filled with sediment so bring a rigid nut tool for cleaning.

name: Sergeant's Fingerline Crack
description: On the left side of the wall you'll see a splitter crack starting 5 to 6 feet of of the ground. Follow this crack up the the first ledge between the two flakes then to the top.

name: Who Stole Your Shoes
description: Start below the 10 foot section below the middle largest crack. This route has 3 variations (left, mid and right) all of the same grade. Bring a large cam to protect below the ledge and small cams and tricams for the lower and upper section.

name: J Bud
description: Fun climb that follows a natural crack in the rock from the bottom to near the top. There is a low left foot for the start and the rest are a bit sketchy, but it makes for a fun climb The crack ends at the top and there is a series of three horizontal protrusions that can be used as an edge, crimp, or pinch. Climb is a top out.

name: Still Breathing
description: Climb that is to the left of J-Bud and requires using the arête for the left hand and the crack/top pinches for the right. Climb requires some fun, but high feet.

name: Louisiana Flake
description: Begin standing with hands on good edges, and climb straight up to a sloped top out

name: Slabby's
description: Begin with hands on good ledge (furthest right), and traverse left on the overhang. Down-climb before the pit. Sloping ramp is off for feet until you reach the down-climb.

name: All's Well That Ends Well
description: Start with undercling pinchers on the left rising crack, and use tiny crimpers to climb into crack and top out.

name: Cornered
description: Begin matched on good hand pocket, and move up and right to top out. Cool, yet only a few moves.

name: Windblown Arete
description: Start on high left crimp with right hand at head height on the right arête, and climb straight up. Moves get trickier the higher you go.

name: Luigi's Crack
description: Begin problem at the large angled block 5 feet below the main cliff. Climb up this and onto the ledge that runs below the most of the face. From here, Climb straight up and into diagonal, right leaning crack that splits all the way up. Very tall, unprotected climb. If insecure about the bold climb, set up a rope. Beautiful quality however, and the climbing is easy.

name: Detroit Rock City
description: A long, left-to-right traverse of the featured face. Very footwork intensive problem. Top out straight up once you run out of boulder to traverse.

name: Fanger Slapper
description: Begin under the overhang with a high left hand. Move right through razor sharp holds and top out at the right end of the boulder. Several flakes have fallen off the lower part of the climb, which now leaves the climber with several options for footholds. Sharp rock, but awesome powerful movement.

name: Freak Gasoline Doppelgänger
description: If you can't climb slab you will swear on your mother's life this is NOT v1. Make a move off good holds to greet a blank face. Move up through tiny crimps, divots and knobs until the rock levels off. Jog to the top. The small tree behind the climber provides an opportunity to bail at any time. Exciting!!

name: Pac Man's Lunch
description: Great, easy problem. Begin in the center of the boulder, with hands in horizontal, right rising crack. Climb up the boulder however you want (left arete, face only, right arete and face, etc.) and grab the jug directly over the top to top out.

name: Spiderman Cave
description: Start in cave with hands in sloped pockets and move up to lip. Then traverse right on the lip to top out.

name: Under the Sliding Roof
description: Start at the far left of the boulder on a jug/sloper, traverse right, and exit at the right end of the roof.  Use slopers and hand jams under the roof, and either thin feet or heel hooks.

name: Uptown Boulder Arete
description: Start in the lowest left slot/crack under the Uptown Crack.  Move straight up the arete

name: Uptown Crack
description: Start with hands low in the higher, thinner crack and climb up to top out on the horn. Committing moves higher up, as the problem is decently high.

name: Bear Scramble
description: Start with the hands in the obvious crack line, about halfway of the the possible traverse listed within Legend of Korra. Jugs, crimps, and foot/leg jam is included! Top-out is the crux.

name: I am Legend
description: Start in the space between the two halves of Legend Rock with two hands on a one pad crimp. Move left around the corner on pleasant crimps, followed by a really big move past the blank section to a jug. Topout is easy.Variations: Go straight up the corner after the first move left. This would be necessary if you can't reach the long move, and is quite hard on its own. Another great problem is to keep going left along the crimps and topping out up the arete (bad landing!) or past the tree.

name: Legend of Korra
description: On the far right of the boulder, start low and go up the jugs. Tons of variations depending on how far right and low you start. Traversing left and right on the huge ledge is a good warmup.

name: Minuteman Hurdle
description: Come to the front with the tree to the right of the face. Find the two upside-down triangle natural cuts near the crack line. Below, there is a foothold slightly above knee height. The initial move will be a jump up, then use the cuts as footholds (foot jamming?). There are occasional holds all around, but it's mainly leg strength. Once you get up, it's just a ledge swing-over. You can also use the tree occasionally, if need be.

name: Minuteman Left
description: Start on the left side where there is an easy ledge for your feet. Find two holds above and traverse to the high foot start from Minuteman Hurdle. Top out from there.

name: Corner Climb
description: Start in the corner where there are a bunch of slightly downward slanted ledges and follow them up to the top. Shortest way up the rock.

name: Jumpstart Jabberwock
description: Start on the backside of the boulder where the wall is completely blank. Back up, then jump off of a small ledge at knee height to grab onto a piece of rock about 10 feet up the rock. Awesome move. Then go straight up and top out.

name: Middle Line
description: Go directly in the middle of the rock and follow the series of good holds up to a somewhat sketchy top out due to the height.

name: Mombert Mentality
description: Start sitting with your left hand in a small horizontal crack and your right hand on a juggy  side pull. Move up the right side of the rock, lean into a slopey side pull, move up to a jug, then top out on some slopers. Any holds on the face to the right of the arete are off.

name: Mushroom Flake
description: Start with a slopey side pull on your right and mantle with your left. Move into a gaston, then reach up to the mushroom top shaped flake. Top out from there.

name: Rob Ford's Crack
description: Follow the largest vertical crack in the boulder up to the top.

name: Slabby Patty
description: Start with a side pull on your left, and a sloper/crimp on the right. Make your way up to some small crimps and then a pocket/side pull. Top out or match your hands on the top.

name: Sto's Ladder
description: Lots of good holds for your feet and hands all the way up. Only V1 because your about 16-20 feet off the ground at the top and it's pretty scary topping out sometimes.

name: Broken Skin
description: I have not been able to complete this project so the grade is unknown but if I had to take a shot in the dark I'd say it is V4-6. Start inside the cave from a sit start and make your way up. You need to slap your hand onto the sloping lip of the rock and it is VERY sharp in some places.

name: Broken Skin 2
description: Start to the left of the cave of Broken Skin and make your way up. Very sharp rock, you may cut your hands if you fall.

name: Smokey Rock
description: Start on the slightly overhanging side of the larger boulder and make your way up using some small holds and the arete.

name: Warm Up Slab
description: Massive slab to the right of Broken Skin. Good for warming up.

name: Wolf Spider Rock
description: Start sitting down at a clear starting point and make your way up the rock however you want. Watch out for wolf spiders. Also pretty sharp rock and bad landing area.

name: Conor Oberst
description: start in between the rocks on the left end of the larger boulder. Sit Start on okay crimps right under the ‘crescent moon’ feature. Go into the moon shaped crimp and up to the left.

name: Corner Overhang
description: Potential for a higher grade problem with a lower/sit start. Start with your left hand on the lip where you put your right hand for Harold’s Razors. Start with your right hand out to a jug, move up past the lip and up the arete.

name: Harold's Boulder
description: Start with your left hand on the hold in the overhang and your right hand above the lip in a jug. After a series of dynamic moves to the shelf, make your way up without using the arete.

name: Harold’s Boulder Right Start
description: Start with your left hand in the jug you put your right hand in at the start of Harold's Boulder. Put your right hand on a pretty crappy sloper just above the lip and kick your left leg out to get a heel hook and match the jug with 2 fingers. Make your way up from there.

name: Harold’s Razors
description: Start on the slopey lip and head straight up into some small and sharp holds. Move up the face, right arete off.

name: Queasy
description: Start with your feet in the lowest horizontal crack and your hands on the ledge with the plants coming out of it. Move up to the next crack then up to the arete to the top. The ledge to the left of the face is off.

name: Stegosaurus
description: Start with your feet all the way at the bottom of the overhang in the smaller boulder, your left hand in a crack right above the lip, and your right hand on a sloping piece of rock on the lip. Jump up about 2-3 feet to a jug with your left hand, make another dynamic move to a jug off to the right, then pull yourself up. Super fun and cool looking moves.

name: Stretch Your Legs
description: Start all the way on the lowest and leftmost part of the boulder on the side to the left of Harold's Boulder. Traverse across the boulder to the right without using ANY parts of the top of the boulder until you can reach the highest point.

name: Warm Up
description: Start on the right most end of the closer side of the larger boulder (in between the rocks). Traverse across without using any holds on the top of the rock until you reach the highest point.

name: Defund the police
description: Start to the left of Sunset Rock on the blank face. Move up to a sharp crimp then up to the sloper.

name: First Line
description: Start with your hands in the horizontal crack and pull yourself up on some decent crimps until you can top out. Try not to use any of the rock on the left. Great rock, slanted landing area.

name: Ponch's Wall
description: Start in the middle and make your way up the slab. Requires some technical moves on small holds. Stop at the juggy square hold under the horizontal crack that separates the two faces of rock.

name: Satan's Toe
description: This is probably my favorite problem in the area. Start under the overhang where there is an obvious undercling. Make some dynamic moves to the lip of the overhang where there are good holds. The crux is the mantle onto the lip because it is at a weird angle and there are hardly any holds to pull yourself up with.

name: Sunset Rock
description: Start on the right side of the rock, reach up to an awkward undercling/pinch, then after a couple easier moves you can grab the arete and top out.

name: "I Sold My Skin To The Devil"
description: Problem is located to the left of "the layback". Start with good holds on the horizontal crack, move up and to the left along the sloping arete.

name: cheatstone
description: a short fun wall with a built in cheatstone and an incredible jug halfway up

name: Covfefe
description: Start sitting with your hands on the shelf near the ground. Make your way up to the right to a series of diagonally oriented crimps. Follow them about until you reach a good side pull. Go up and to the left to a crimp, then top out.

name: Fish Hook
description: Start sitting down with your hands on two decent crimps. Pull yourself onto the rock then use some small holds to make your way up to the pocket 2/3 of the way up. Hook your finger inside inside of it then top out. You cannot use the cheat stone or the jug in the middle of the rock.

name: Fruit Loops
description: Start sitting down to the left of the cheat stone. Put your left hand on the left side of the boulder and your right on a nice hold on the right. Pull yourself up (may require a heel hook) and make your way to the amazing jug in the middle of the rock. You cannot use the cheat stone or it’s pretty much the same as the original problem.

name: Heel Hooker Direct
description: Start on the ledge with your left hand and on a crimp near the base of the rock with your right. Move into the horizontal crack then do a dynamic move straight to the top, or use the quarter pad crimp as an intermediary. You cannot use the arete.

name: Heel Hooker ²
description: Start sitting down with your left hand on the left most jug in the horizontal crack and your right in a slanted crimp near the base of the rock. Use a heel hook to move your right hand into the crack then use another heel hook on the arete to make your way up to a crimp in the middle of the rock. Grab the arete then it’s easy climbing.

name: Indian Overhang
description: start on a rock near the base and reach high for good holds to an easy face and climb through to the top

name: Indian Overhang Low Start
description: Start from a nearly sitting position on Indian Overhang and use a heel hook around the right side of the rock  to make your way up.

name: Jupiter
description: Start on the obvious jug that is just to the left of the vertical crack that splits the boulder. Proceed to traverse left across the horizontal seam in the rock. After you reach the area where the seam turns the corner go straight up and top out. Happy sends space cadets!!

name: Layback Right Arete
description: Self-explanatory title. Getting on the start can be a bit tricky. Once you're off the ground stick to the right side of the arête to top out. If you want to do a variation of the problem ou can traverse to the layback crack to top out.

name: the layback
description: follow the crack all the way up, layback may be required

name: matts wall
description: short wall, simple and fun

name: Project: Gritty Traverse
description: A technical traverse on slopey crimps and small footholds. Start with two hands in the large crack and keep moving left. Not sure where the top out should be, I haven't gotten that far! Still a project but feels around V4/5.

name: the slope
description: a slanted side with very little to grab on to

name: Closeout
description: Start just right of the wave. Left hand side pull and right hand crimp. Throw directly up to some slopers. Big moves to gain the lip, then dive into crack and ascend the highball slab.

name: Shipsterns Bluff
description: Follow slab on right of boulder straight up.

name: Triple Overhead
description: Start in the barrel and follow crack system out small roof. Pull roof and stand ontop of the wave. Here is where you encounter the death flake (hence R rating). Flake is secured, but don't pull too hard and you might find yourself laying on the ground clutching a 70 lb boulder. Don't forget your head game for this one.

name: Tucky
description: Start on the bottom left ledge and traverse over right until the end of the protruding square and then up to a triangle piece witch is the top. then walk over and around the right side of the boulder back to the trail.

name: High Road
description: Marked out in yellow. Starting on the US, a jug around the corner on the lake-facing side of Crackhead, traverse slightly left and use a heel hook and a side pull in order to get yourself over to the pictured side of Crackhead. Pull yourself upright, and get your hands in the crack heading slightly downwards towards the ground. From there, get your right foot into the horizontal crack system next to/in front of you and reach for a good but small semi-crimp ~3 ft above you. Once held, traverse towards your left on Crackhead and continue until you cannot move any farther left.  This route can be particularly wet after a rainstorm, so I would advise leaving at least 2 dry days between an attempt and poor weather.

name: Low Road
description: Marked out in red. The route starts on the lake-facing side of Crackhead. Find the US, a descent jug to match your hands on, then traverse left, where, in order to get to the side the picture presents, your must use a heel hook and a side pull on the pictured side. Pull yourself up on your heel, and get your hands into the crack heading slightly down, towards the ground on your left. Traverse until the end of the crack, where you should use a side pull/crimp in order to reach a jug hold, from which the climb directly up crackhead should be relatively easy. Top out.

name: Broken Typewriter
description: Marked in yellow. Start at LS, and traverse past the lower sapling. From there, move directly up to the top of the boulder. Top out.

name: Gollum's Pass
description: Marked in orange. Start at RS, then move up the diagonal crack all the way up to the higher sapling. From there, move up the diagonal crack to the right of the sapling to the top. Top out.

name: Typewriter
description: Marked in red. Start at LS, from which traverse right past the lower sapling. Once past, climb up a rock tier and proceed moving left, towards the higher sapling. Once directly next to the sapling, begin the final ascent, staying on the small diagonal crack leading to the top. Top out.

name: Budding Boulder
description: Start directly left of the start for Heartthrob with a sit a start, make your way left through part of the budding tree and top out a little bit right of the highest point of the rock.

name: Cupid's Ladder
description: Marked out in red in the picture. Route starts with hands matched on US. From there, head 5 ft to the right, then climb directly up through the heart and top out.

name: Heartthrob
description: Marked out in yellow in the picture. Start at US, then head left. The "checkpoint" is the patio low to the ground to your left, on which you must get both your feet to send this route. From there, head directly up the wall, passing over the part of the wall bulging out (like a chest with a heart beating hard). Top out.

name: Mantling Maple
description: Start to the left of Budding Boulder and go through the tree and top out to the left of the highest point on the rock.

name: Old Flame
description: Marked out in orange in the picture. Start at US, then traverse left, passing the heart and staying low on the wall. Begin ascending once you approach the moss to your right. Top out.

name: Bean Boulder
description: Sit start on the lowest flake about 2-3 feet off the ground, move up to the shelf then pull onto the face without using the left arete. Climb the highball slab to the top.

name: Flake On Me
description: Crack left of the small overhang.

name: Cornerstone
description: Start on the jug to the right of the corner then go straight into the corner and up

name: Split Open and Melt
description: Straight up the big crack

name: Stretch Armstrong
description: Start on the same jug as corner stone and stretch out right to a slot. Go over two bulges and top out.

name: V0 Slab
description: Slab on the left side of Stretch Armstrong Boulder. Go up left last the tree.

name: L.D.M.
description: Lock off. Dead point. Mantel. Start on two obvious wide spread hand hold. Look for a small nub or two to get your feet up. From the lock off find your balance to grab the top lip. Get ready for a sloper too out. Once topping out, look dead ahead to see the boulders name sake.

name: Missed Connection
description: Start at a lower side pull jug hold and make your way up the shallow crack to the top-out

name: Solaris
description: The green route on the picture start with two small crimps traverses left a bit and then goes up to the top out.  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wWpiXEwtGC0

name: Face Time
description: x

name: Fuck Your Face
description: x

name: Mossy Face
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Erratical
description: Start on low chalked jug in center of boulder. Traverse out right, then hit the slopey lip. From here, work your way across the lip and get to the crack system way out right. Hand hold broke unfortunately, so i'll bump it up to v5+.

name: Hungarian Breakfast
description: Start on the lowest end of the left side of the rock with a sit start. Make your way up the first horizontal crack then down to the chalk covered shelf. From there go right and enter the juggy start of Whale Chunder and make your way into the crack to the top.

name: Slab Side
description: It starts with right hand on a sloper piece and left hand on a not so obvious little side pull.  The finish is basically right above the start. Its a fun little climb and its significantly easier than the other routes on this boulder.

name: Whale Chunder
description: Start on the juggy shelf, move right into the horizontal crack under the lip, then put a right hand in the vertical crack above the lip and use a sloper then a layback to make your way up and top out.

name: Digglett Dig
description: If you like high tension and slopers then this is for you. Start sitting at the bottom of the flake and make your way upwards by squeezing on either side. Find the higher of the two low left feet and slap the right hand while toe hooking the right side to move your left hand above the rock. Topout using a series of delicate, desperate moves

name: Dragon's Back
description: Interesting series of friction moves on tiny crystals an micro crimps. Start standing and get high feet to hit an undercling. Lean right and hit nonexistant holds to move your feet up before finding the high crack. Top out as in Tiny Pants.

name: Stairway to Heaven
description: Easy and fun. This is a good warm up before heading deeper onto the trail. Start just to the left of the arete that faces the forest and head straight up! Exit on the side of the trail.

name: Tiny Pants
description: So easy you can do it in tennis shoes! Starting on the righthand flake of the crack, employ paybacks and foot jams till you reach the top of the righthand flake. Exit off the top of the right flake.

name: Watch Out For Bears!
description: Stand start with your left hand on the obvious crack and the right up high. Goes straight up.

This is the yellow route on the topo. The first clip is easy to clip up to set and clip a bolt on the other side of the short arete and then head for the hardest move of pulling up to the next bolt. then walk over the ledge to the bolted anchor.

name: 39th Tra-Di
description: Starting holds from a crouch position with right hand to the obvious jug, left hand to the crimp slightly lowered (as pictured), and foot holds a mix of a smear and tiny ledges to the left. Climb up to the crack line and traverse left towards the small dihedral. Once in the dihedral, use various crimp holds to top out into the center angle of the dihedral WITHOUT using the arrete on the left.

name: NAW
description: Named after some graffiti on the side during the time of FA..  From standing, hands start on respective side holds on left and right (marked in picture) with a little spot for your right foot on the deep right corner along the crack   Using the ledge descending down from the left probably bumps this down to a V0-V1 but is off for the V3.   *after rain, this face in particular tends to take a day or two to dry up completely. Be safe

name: urban sketch slab
description: Obvious lean/stand start with sketchy concrete pockets and solid brick holds all the way up to the rock ledge about 12 feet up if balanced correctly.  Boulder on both sides are OFF for v2 (ON for easier beta)  ***V-Project*** climb all the way up to the fence (roughly 20ft total from the initial problem start). Please take extreme care and definitely have a spotter when finding reliable beta due to some of the concrete holds coming loose.

name: Circumcision
description: Squat/Sit start on the right side of the ledge, get the good jug with both hands, and use some bulges on the slab to climb straight up it.

name: Circumference
description: Sit start left of "Circumcision" on a right-hand pinch and a left-hand crimp. Cross into the jug flak and finish up the v4.

name: Praise The Phrase
description: Sit start on a right-hand weird side-pull and a left-hand crimp undercling. Link into "Words are Weapons".

name: Round Bout Stand
description: Squat start on a left-hand side-pull, and a right had sloper around the arete. One move to the lip.

name: Thing 1
description: Stand start on two sidepull crimps and go up.

name: Thing 2
description: Sit start on a low large-good flake. Climb up and left to the same topout as "Thing 1".

name: TWENETYFOURSEVEN
description: Sit start the same as "Thing 2", but the large sidepull and crimps along it are off. Climb below them to the left-hand gaston (Right-hand start of "Thing 1") before topping out.

name: Words are Weapons
description: Start on the obvious crimps on the face, go out right doing a cool lock off and top out early.
TRAIL WALL. SIT START ON FACE TO LEFT OF APPROACH TRAIL, SHORT THIN FACE ELIMINATE CHIMNEY ON LEFT AND OUTSIDE CORNER ON RIGHT
NEAR WALL. TRAVERSE ENTIRE WALL. DO NOT USE TOP OF CLIFF. DO NOT USE LARGE LEDGES. START RIGHT OF APPROACH TRAIL AND END AT THE BACK WALL.
NEAR WALL. THIN FACE JUST LEFT OF BIG CORNER
NEAR WALL. SHORT CRACK.
NEAR WALL. BEAR-HUG RIGHT SIDE OF ARETE
NEAR WALL. THINNEST PART OF WIDE FACE.
SECOND WALL. FACE LEFT OF CRACK.
SECOND WALL. FACE RIGHT OF CRACK WITHOUT CRACK
SECOND WALL. LEFT SIDE OF ARETE USING JUGS.
SECOND WALL. JUGS ON ARETE. ANGLE RIGHT USING THIN MOVES TO SKETCHY TOP OUT. ARETE OFF ROUTE.
BACK WALL. Thin face between flake system on right and 1.5 feet from left edge. Eliminate good footholds in seam near ground.
BACK WALL. Flake/seam system in center of face

name: [Redacted]
description: (V1) just left of right facing corner using corner to hug to the jug and top out. No feet on large center block. (V0-) Using feet on large center block.

name: CRACK ITSELF
description: SECOND WALL. CRACK CLIMB.

name: STRETCH
description: BACK WALL. sit start left arête at end of wall. Move right on open thin face using only vertical side of corner. Move to open sloper mid-way across wall and traverse right to top out. Do not use top of wall for traverse.

name: Beef Traverse
description: Strenuous. Move onto the face right of the cave and hand traverse left following an obvious line of jugs. Pass over the cave to its left side. Now reverse to the starting point, or for a superior workout, drop down and follow 'Exit Cave Left' back up to a jug line, then traverse right to the starting point.

name: Epidemic
description: Start with the left hand on the vertical crimp/pinch and the right hand on a sharp half-pad crimp. Make a big move up to a sloping rail, and while maintaining good foot/body tension slap your way to the top!

name: Highlawn Cave Left Crack
description: Start from the same horizontal crack as 'Highlawn Cave Lip Traverse'. Move right to the first vertical crack and climb to the summit.

name: Highlawn Project #1
description: RATING UNKNOWN. Start in the cave and climb out the widest part of the ceiling to a series of painful finger lock in a vertical crack. Destined to be a very big number problem, at least V10 (Neil Sloane 2000).

name: Highlawn Project #2
description: RATING UNKNOWN. Start on the jugs in the horizontal crack just left of the left end of the ceiling's lip. Traverse right along as line of holds just above the ceiling's lip. Stay below the handholds used in 'Beef Traverse'.

name: Icarus
description: Begin with left hand in the lowest finger lock and right hand a long wingspan out right. Lift off and soar straight up to the rim, pumping hard to avoid the fate of Icarus.

name: Left Crack Cave Start
description: Start in the back left corner of the cave, left wall is off for hands. Move to an undercling, then make your way to the small jug below the finger pocket and larger jug. Go straight up from there.

name: Pandemic
description: I've been pretty rusty and am not too sure of the grade. It may be more difficult depending on ape index, as the holds you can use will change. Start deep in the cave on a good undercling. Make a series of moves on the various underclings and sharp crimps to make your way to the start of Epidemic. The most proud line in the cave, and takes a while to decipher because of the many available poor holds.

name: Black and White Cookie
description: traverse left to right starting with smoother white granite and moving right, toward darker, easier blocks. white blocks are much harder and more techy, grey blocks are just pumpy.

name: Charlie Don't Surf
description: begin traverse on corner and make moderate/easy moves for about 10 feet. crux is blank blocks with no cracks.  climb up then left using reachy ledges, ridiculously shallow pockets and a thin crimpy edge. second crux is less strenous but also tricky.  1 resting block between the 2 hard problems

name: Chiron Beta Prime
description: link up of the jumping jack flash and gawker traverse (backwards). THIS ROUTE HAS BEEN DESTROYED BY THE INSTALLATION OF CITY BIKES

name: Gawker Traverse
description: THIS ROUTE HAS BEEN DESTROYED BY THE INSTALLATION OF CITY BIKES

name: jumpin jack flash
description: sustained and pumpy like most climbs in this area.  no distinct crux but only 2 good rests to chalk up.  starts on decent sized ledge and traverses right to all the way to the corner of coles and 6th.

name: Picasso’s Zipper
description: The start is on a block that looks like a face in a Picasso painting. Must climb the zig zag crack all the way to the top. No other holds allowed, crack only.

name: Bridge of Sighs
description: This route begins low on the right side of Flake 1. Feet are two inches of the ground. Right hand goes on a palmy side of the arete in a dark alcove. Left hand is in positive hold in an alcove. Left foot moves into a hidden hold down and left. Left hand moves to a one digit ledge a bit left of the alcove. Move up and left a bit with the right hand into a vertical slot/layback. Bring your feet up right onto a chockstone. Move the hands up and left a bit to horizontal edge/pinch. Move the feet up on ledges and then reach up and right with right hand to a small edge. This is a very claustrophobic spot with the main cliff right behind your head. Lunge up to an indistinct horizontal ( it's very dark at this point in the problem. almost like a cave). This is where the problem ends although there is no clear finishing point.

name: Chunk! No, Captain Chunk!
description: The crux is the first move from the start. Start is a sit start using the obvious crimps, 2 hand start, and feet off to the left. From there reach up with right hand to small block. Step over with right foot to make next move. several more moves to good top out.

name: Garden State Parkway
description: This problem goes up the outside arete of Flake 1 which is located above the Inchworm Boulder. This Flake is about 25 feet tall and rests against the main cliff face directly below the Tower.  This problem goes up holds on the arete or just inside of the outer edge of the arete for 25 feet until you can pull up onto a ledge. Some of the holds are insecure and one of the crux moves occurs when the boulderer is making a horizontal move above a sharp rock sticking up out of the ground.

name: Grabbin a Dragon's Tail
description: Around the corner from Romano's Arete. This is the first completed problem on the underside of Flake 1. Left side of the arete is off limits. Begin standing with a right hand high in a small layback and a left hand in a side pull. Pull onto the problem by stepping first with the left and bringing the right into a heel hook in a good 6 inch corner. Pop up with the right to a higher layback in the same seam system. Lunge with the left to the top edge(very sharp). At this point the main cliff face is only about three feet behind you but don't use it. Reach over the top to higher holds, bring your feet up and pull up and over the top.

name: The Inchworm Boulder
description: This route is on the prominent buttress of rock jutting out of the hill. The Inchworm boulder is only about 40 feet from a partially paved path. There are a number of straight up problems that have been done in the V0 range.

name: The Inchworm Traverse
description: This route is on the prominent buttress of rock jutting out of the hill. The Inchworm boulder is only about 40 feet from a partially paved path. Begin the problem on the left side of the boulder. Step onto the boulder in a shallow left facing alcove and then reach up to a jug. Move right onto two small crimps below the main break which runs across the boulder. Stay below this main break until the very end of the boulder. After the crimps continue to move right passing a jug and then go to a sloper and a crimp before lunging to a hold on the corner with the right hand. Avoid the small boulder below this problem at the end of the traverse. Now move up to the break and a stance. The problem is over.

name: Left Side Arete
description: This is a nice high ball problem that isn't filled with technical difficulty, but it requires some commitment to finish. A good way to work on your arete climbing skills. On the left side of Flake 2 begin by placing your left foot onto a ledge and left hand on a low hold. Both holds are facing Right Side Arete. Step up and reach for a good hold around the corner to the right with your right hand. This is a very positive hold. Step up and reach left for an unseen hold. Move up with the right foot now standing on the positive hold around the corner to the right. Move your left hand up a bit more staying on the arete (This is the arete closest to the overhanging underside of Flake 2). Paste your right foot on a small sloping edge on the underside of Flake 2. Step up on that hold and reach a long way for a horizontal break and relief. You're not done yet. Now traverse on the horizontal break to the right on the overhanging section of Flake 2. Go all the way around to the right side Arete of Flake 2 and then downclimb to a boulder and off.

name: Lord of the Flies
description: This is a really fun problem which runs up the overhanging underside of Flake 2. It begins on two low holds just to the right of the Left Side Arete. Using the arete or the large positive hold mentioned in Left Side Arete is off limits for this problem. Begin with hands crossed in low holds about three feet off the ground. Reach up with the right for a small positive hold. Left hand goes up to a layback feature. Step up onto sloping ledge and then reach long with the right up to a triangular pinch hold. Left hand comes up to a hold next to the right hand. Now comes the committing moves: Reach up into a left facing arete for a small layback with your left hand. Hike your feet up and reach right to the arete or best available hold. Then reach up to the high horizontal break mentioned in Left Side Arete. Move around the corner and enjoy the view.

name: Muddy Turtles
description: This route goes up the middle of the side of Flake 1. Any ascentionists should know ahead of time that some work will be needed to clear this route of the debris from a tree that fell in 2011. The tree is about 6 feet in circumference and blocks the opening moves of the problem. Having said that, if someone puts in the time this is the best route of the area and will reward those who put in the effort. Begin with the left hand on a short left facing layback hold. The right is on a large horizontal. this is a very low start and right behind you is that sharp rock mentioned in Garden State Parkway description. Pull onto the rock and move into a heel hook for the left. Move your left hand over to another hold. Pop for a one digit ledge for the right. Adjust your feet on a small hold. Move the left up to a large sloper. Hike your feet up and pop for a sloping vertical layback with the left. Then hike the feet up further and pop for an insecure layback higher up. Stabilize and move up to the top. Using holds on the right arete is out of bounds. Reach up and over the top and pull up to the same spot as Garden State Parkway.  Descend using the metal pipe going down the main cliff and holds on Flake 1 and the main cliff.

name: Nick Arete
description: Begin as Yin and Yang but this time when you pull onto the route using the same holds, slap around the corner for a good layback hold around the corner to the right. Heel hook far around the corner with the right foot. reach around to the right side of the arete with left hand. Pull up and keep hands just to the right or left side of the arete. Same for feet. Follow to the large ledge and then down climb.  Although this climb shares many of the same holds as Yin and Yang, this is a very different problem because the climber is often pulling to the right where Yin and Yang require the climber to pull off to the left.

name: Right Side Arete
description: This problem ascends the right side of a boulder that leans up against Flake 1. It may at one time have been part of the Flake but is now separate from the main Flake. There is a sit start or a standing start to this problem. The sit start adds no difficulty, just one more move. Begin standing with right hand palming the arete on the far right side of Flake 1 about 6 feet away from Bridge of Sighs. Step with the right foot onto the arete and reach for a clean horizontal break at about 9 feet. Grab the break with both hands. Move the right foot up on the arete with the left foot on some small edges around and left on the overhanging side of the block. Reach the right hand about three feet up onto the arete to a palmy hold. Bring the right foot up to a dimple on the arete. Pull up and lunge with the left to a small horizontal break four feet above a bit left of the arete. You can continue up but there are no more difficulties and there is lots of Poison Ivy on top. From the small horizontal with the left, down climb or drop onto pads. This is fun little route that is balancy.

name: Right Side Flake 2
description: On the left side of Flake 2 go up the arete using holds to the right and left of the corner.  When you get to the horizontal break at 20 feet, then traverse around to the right on the underside of the boulder and around to the other side.  Downclimb  to a boulder and then to the ground

name: Romano Alternate
description: This problem was first eyed by Rich Romano on a visit in 2009. This problem begins on the Inchworm boulder below the Inchworm Traverse. Where the Rock Buttress comes out from the ground there is a section of rock. Begin this problem with your hands on the large flat holds and your feet on two smudges. Reach with the left hand out and up onto the roof of the Inchworm Boulder. There is a flake here to use as a layback with the left. Lean out using the left and reach with the right to a sloping edge. Pinch it and reach out over the roof to slopers. Match above the roof and then move right two small moves on better holds. Keeping your feet on holds below the roof (the boulder below the Inchworm if you can). After the two small moves your hands should be in a shallow left facing corner. Gather your feet below you and lunge up and slightly right to a two inch flat edge. You have now joined the Inchworm Traverse.  Continue as with the Traverse to the end.

name: Romano's Arete
description: This route begins in a sit down start on the inside arete of Flake 1. The left hand uses holds in common with Muddy Turtles and the right hand begins on a hold around the corner on the overhanging side of Flake 1. Begin for the left on the one inch horizontal hold also used by Muddy Turtles. Right hold is on a small break around the corner. Pull onto the problem. Make a blind slap with the left into the layback used by MT. Move right up to a more secure hold. Hike up the feet, stand up and then pop the right into a very small undercling on the right side of the arete. Make a slap with the left to a higher layback. Move the feet up again and then move up to the top same as GSP and MT.

name: Unfinished problem
description: This is a great looking traverse that begins just to the right of Romano's Arete. Begin on overhanging horizontal holds that moves into a shallow overhanging corner. This part has been done already. Move around the corner on smaller horizontals and continue to the other end of Flake 1. This may be the hardest problem at Garrett Mtn when completed. This problem is on clean rock and features some interesting holds. It's been tried for 15 years and a first ascent by some talented boulderer would be a welcome relief to this reporter who put in hours failing to complete this problem.

name: Yin and Yang
description: This is a really fine route with some interesting moves and good holds. The problem gets harder higher up and you need to have your wits about you when committing to the finishing moves. Begin in a sit start with your right hand pinching the right arete of Flake 2 and your left on a chalked side pull/pinch grip on the face. Place your feet on some large holds inches off of the ground and pull on. Slap up higher on the arete with the right and make powerful move up and left to an edge on the face for the left hand. Move your right foot onto a small, hard to see edge and lunge up to pinch a loose block on the arete. Bring your left foot up and bring the left hand up to a small edge about two feet left of the arete. Reach up into an alcove for a layback with the right hand. Step around the arete to the right for a good right foothold. Then move up and put feet on some small edges. Left hand goes put to a small right facing corner for a layback. Stabilize. Reach up and to better holds near or at the horizontal break. Move around to the right about 6 feet below the top. The problem is over. Downclimb.

name: El Bambi
description: To the left of VO Hero. Two hand sit start, left hand on the side rail, right hand on the underclinge. Be careful there is a lose hold near the top left.

name: V0 Hero
description: Good warm up problem.

name: Kiwi Shoe Polish
description: Route begins on the corner of the outcropping where there is a nice flat step. Step on it, From here it is a straight shot to the top with one wrinkle, no hands. From the start to the top out no hands are allowed.

name: The Melon Man
description: Start right hand on a small 2-3 finger crimp, left hand on a horrible pinch, and put a heel out left before pulling off the ground (you might need to fold a pad to reach the heel). Throw left to a decent sloper, and bump out right. Go directly up for an easy top out.  I'm not entirely sure if this is an FA, but considering the lack of any info at all online I'm just assuming.

name: Salaami
description: A nice easy warm up problem at the entrance to the area.

name: Striker's Revenge
description: Stricker's Revenge is a burly problem that starts on a slight overhang. It is an obvious start on the rocky crimp. work hands up along the remaining crimps and keep feet on the face. Then  top out over a slopper filled slab with barely any recognizable holds. Caution, large boulder right in front of climb make sure to have  a crash pad and spotter.

name: Cospito's Corner
description: Small corner warm up problem. Start on obvious two hand start and work your way leaning towards the right. Top of is one of the better in the area but still sloppy. Make sure to have crash pad and spotter if needed.

name: After the Knee
description: Same start as "Bend the Knee". Follow the crimps to the left and make the same power move to the decent jug. Instead of falling into the sloper, this time, summon all the tension in your body to bring your hand to the top of the boulder. Once you grab the top, shuffle a bit to the right of the boulder to find the lip and top out.

name: Battle of the Bulge
description: Project in the Entrance Boulders. Start on the undercling side pull on the left, keep feet on the face. Work hands over a series of small crimps and throw to the slopper on the right, bring up left hand and top out...in theory. Still being projected guestimated as a V4/5

name: Before the Knee
description: Same start as "Bend the Knee". Go up to the same crimp (or the slightly worse crimp above it) and instead of moving left, dyno directly to the finish of "Bend the Knee". Top out the same way.

name: Bend the Knee
description: Start on a left hand crimp and a right hand slopey side pull. Move up to a decent crimp. Move left through a series of crimps. Do not use the ledge. After you get to the last crimp, set feet and make a large thrown to a jug on the left side of the boulder. Intermediary side pull or small crimp may be used to bump. Once at the jug, drop hand into the side sloper. Stick in a cheeky knee bar and throw to the right most edge. You may top out using the separate right boulder for feet.

name: Break The Knee
description: Sit start to Bend The Knee. Start left hand on jug, right hand on sidepull about level with head, and feet out left. Bump right hand up to small edge on the arete. Throw for block just right of the left hand start hold for Bend The Knee. Right hand up to decent crimp (same as 1st move of BTK). Rest of climb goes the same way as Bend The Knee but mantle to top out instead of using the ledge to the right.  If this has been done before please let me know.

name: Chunk! No Captain Chunk!
description: The crux is the first move from the start. Start is a sit start using the obvious crimps, 2 hand start, and feet off to the left. From there reach up with right hand to small block. Step over with right foot to make next move. several more moves to good top out.  Caution: downed tree right at the base of the boulder

name: Hey You Guys!
description: Start to the leftest most part of the lip from the start of Chunk! No Captain Chunk! Work your way across and follow the route above.

name: Free Willy
description: This is a fun traverse that starts standing with a good match on the left of the High Roller Boulder. Make you way across to the right staying low. Crux move, reach around the right arete for a small side pull crimp. Stand up on the right foot and reach over your head with your left hand to take the nice jug up to the right. Tight core to stop the barn-door at the end just before the final match and then top out.

name: L'eggo-My-Eggo
description: Directly to the left of Cospito's Corner. L'eggo-My-Eggo is a two hand start at about eye level. Next work hands up and throw to small finger pocket. The pocket is deep and gives you enough to work feet into good position to finish the problem. Top out is all sloper. Make sure to have crash pad and spotter if needed.

name: L'eggo-My-Eggo with Syrup
description: Directly to the left of Cospito's Corner, this is the hard variation of the problem. L'eggo-My-Eggo with Syrup has a brutal start, could be used as a side pull or under cling, climbers choice, it still follows the face straight up to the two hands used for the V1 variation. Again used the deep finger pocket to get your feet right. Top out is all sloper. Make sure to have crash pad and spotter if needed.

name: Swamp Ass
description: Sit start directly below the large seam/crack. Work your way up using the seam/crack only. Top out is very easy.

name: Swamp Boogie Traverse
description: Swamp Boogie is the long traverse on the Swamp Thing Wall.  Start on he far left on the jug and work your way up and keep your feet on the the lip that runs the length of the wall. All hands should be on the face, do not use the top of the wall. You can traverse from left to right or top out along the seam on the far right end.

name: Swamp Thing
description: Swamp Thing is the flake on the far right. Start on obvious jug and work your hands up to the next few holds. After you have to hug your way up using the back side of the flake. Use the flake only for both hand and feet.

name: A Flakey Situation
description: Obvious sit start left of the crack. Work your hands into the crack and work your way up until your left foot is on the start. From there work your way out of the crack left and lean across the face. You need to use the dead flake, trust it, it's good. After that work way up to top sloppy top out.

name: The Big Easy
description: The obvious split in the face nearest to the Rocky Hollow Picnic Area. The Big Easy is found on the right side of the split. The start is found in the crack, it is a small nub that accommodates both hands. From there follow the obvious holds up but do not use any holds or feet across the crack.

name: The Not So Big Easy
description: The obvious split in the face nearest to the Rocky Hollow Picnic Area. The Not So Big Easy is found on the left side of the split. The start is found in the crack. Work hands up the inside of the crack and make way to top out. Do not use any holds on the face, feet are ok , do not use holds or feet across the crack.

name: The Wall
description: The Wall can be found to the left of A Flakey Situation. It has an odd start that requires a small dyno to a very generous ledge. From the the more difficult part is working your feet up. Follow obvious ledges after the first and walk your way over the top out. V1 grade given for dyno and height.

name: Bumble
description: Start low on decent holds with a heel on the left block, make a fun powerful move to a good crimp on the right, find good but hard to see feet on the right and make your way to a slopey jug on the left. Move to higher feet and an easy topout from there. Arete/crack on left side is off.

name: Crack to crack traverse
description: Locate the two center cracks. Begin with the crimp on the left hand side, about hip height. There are about 2-3 crimps to the right on the way to the second crack. Last hold on the traverse face (about 4 ft across) is the jut on the bulge, about hip height. Traverse is finished when you can get across the second crack.

name: Moss before the fern
description: Climb the face to the right of the obvious chimney by way of a series of crimps.  Avoid holds on the arete.

name: Chimney sweep
description: High climb (25 ft) but doable V1.  Great for people who can fit in the chimney.

name: Pinky Jam
description: Locate the small cave-y part of the rock next to the chimney.  On the diagonal just above the cave is the starting point of the hands.  Quick move up to some crimps above the head.  There is a triangular slot ("pinky jam") just before the crux.  Crux is the jug about 9 feet up.

name: Miguel's Hill
description: Same start as Miguel's Hill Traverse. Instead of going off to the right for the traverse, go straight up and top out. Jug on left arret is still off. Use the crescent like crimp, pinch, and higher parts of the arret to the top out.

name: Miguel's Hill Traverse
description: Sit start in the small cavey area (to the right of the drop) with a jug and a side pull . Work your way up the face using a crescent like crimp, a pinch, and the higher part of the arretes. Jug on left arret is off. Do a cheeky finger juggle at the triangle like ledge right before the top and move to the right without using the top of the boulder. There is a good undercling around the right side that you can use to get to the right most face and top out with a heel mantle.

name: Over the log
description: same start as Miguel's hill traverse, work your way to the face on the left now using a variety of progressively smaller holds, eventually reaching a good pinch near the top and top out. This one has the fear factor of falling backwards down the ledge so be sure to have pads and a spotter.

name: BAD JOINT BOULDER
description: L->R    V0:left aspect following arête to middle and up   V2:left traverse to middle aspect straight to horn and top out   V1:traverse left to right and top out right   V3:begin on bad joint, finish on 23   22.bad joint V4:sit down start with double on flat jug on left edge of triangle face. Low-traverse right to stance just past right edge, then reverse to starting jug and top out.   V0:right aspect staying to right of horn and top out   23. V2:right traverse left to middle aspect and top out at horn.   V1: right to left traverse top out left following arête

name: Unamed V0
description: Easy climb up the South side of the detached block.

name: Unamed V2
description: Blank slab on the side of a detached block that faces the stream. The staircase on the left side of the start is completely off-route. Toprope Recommended

name: She Sends Sea Sends
description: Unique boulder on a wooden pillar with plastic holds.  Start with hands on the waist-high green and red hold. Shoot up to the red shell and then mantle to the top. Take a minute to enjoy the view at the top before either jumping off or climbing down.

name: Let's see how far we go
description: Start on the low sharp crimp a bit dabby but fun work you way to the jug then follow the lip to the jug on top and top out. Crux is just before the jug.
